                "id": 30,
                "question": "When a Pipe is recreated using the CREATE OR REPLACE PIPE command:\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "The Pipe load history is reset to empty",
                  "B": "The REFRESH parameter is set to TRUE",
                  "C": "Previously loaded files will be ignored",
                  "D": "All of the above"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is A: The Pipe load history is reset to empty. When a Snowflake Pipe is recreated using\nCREATE OR REPLACE PIPE, it essentially drops the existing Pipe and creates a new one with the same name\nand definition. A crucial aspect of a Pipe's operation is its load history, which tracks which files have already\nbeen ingested to prevent duplicate data loading. This history is stored internally and is tied to the specific\nPipe instance. When a Pipe is replaced, this internal history is not carried over to the new instance. Therefore,\nthe newly created Pipe starts with a clean slate, having no record of previously loaded files. This reset means\nthat if the same source data files are still present in the external stage, the new Pipe, unaware of previous\nloads, may ingest them again, leading to potential data duplication. Option B is incorrect because the\nREFRESH parameter isn't directly associated with the replacement of a Pipe but rather with manual refreshes\nof materialized views. Option C is misleading; while the Pipe starts with no load history, it will not \"ignore\"\npreviously loaded files if they are present and trigger a load event. Therefore, only the first option accurately\nreflects the consequence of recreating a Pipe with CREATE OR REPLACE PIPE.For authoritative information\non this topic, refer to the Snowflake documentation:\nCREATE PIPE: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/create-pipe\nPipes: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-load-snowpipe-intro\nUnderstanding Snowpipe History: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-load-snowpipe-managehistory"
              },
              {
                "id": 33,
                "question": "True or False: Snowpipe via REST API can only reference External Stages as source.\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "True",
                  "B": "False"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The statement is False. Snowpipe, when utilizing the REST API, isn't solely restricted to External Stages as\ndata sources. While External Stages (like S3, Azure Blob Storage, or Google Cloud Storage) are a common\nuse case for Snowpipe, the REST API's flexibility allows it to ingest data from other sources as well.Specifically, the API can send data directly in the request body, effectively bypassing the need for prestaging in an external location. This means data can be streamed directly from a client application to\nSnowflake. The REST API interaction involves pushing data in a structured JSON format, which is then parsed\nand loaded into the targeted Snowflake tables. The pipe configuration itself determines the target tables and\nthe transformation rules (if any). Therefore, the REST API method of loading data via Snowpipe provides more\nversatile data ingestion options beyond just externally staged data. This direct loading bypasses external\nstorage locations in many scenarios. This is a key difference between Snowpipe via auto-ingest, which does\nrely on external stages, and REST API Snowpipe.\nSupporting Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Snowpipe REST API: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-loadsnowpipe-rest-apis\nThis document provides comprehensive information about using the REST API for Snowpipe, including the\nability to send data directly within the request body and not rely just on external stages\nSnowflake Documentation on Snowpipe Overview: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-loadsnowpipe-intro\nThis overview helps understand the general mechanism of Snowpipe, and the different ways to ingest data\nusing the Snowpipe Service."
              },
              {
                "id": 69,
                "question": "Which of the following is true of Snowpipe via REST API? (Choose two.)\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "You can only use it on Internal Stages",
                  "B": "All COPY INTO options are available during pipe creation",
                  "C": "Snowflake automatically manages the compute required to execute the Pipe's COPY INTO commands",
                  "D": "Snowpipe keeps track of which files it has loaded"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "C",
                  "D"
