                "explanation": "Here's a detailed justification for why the correct answer to the Snowflake SnowPro\nCore question is C. FILE_EXTENSION:\nWhen unloading data from a Snowflake table to a stage, specifying the correct file\nformat is crucial for generating the desired output, such as a CSV or JSON file. The\nFILE_EXTENSION file format option directly dictates the file extension used for theunloaded data files, effectively determining the file type.\nFILE_EXTENSION and Output Format: This option is what ultimately tells Snowflake\nhow to structure the data written to the stage. If you want a CSV file, the\nFILE_EXTENSION should be set to 'csv'. For JSON, it should be set to 'json'. Snowflake\nwill then format the data accordingly when writing it to the specified stage.\nPARSE_HEADER (A): This option is primarily used when loading data. It instructs\nSnowflake to interpret the first row of a file as column headers. It has no bearing on the\nfile format of unloaded data. Therefore, it is irrelevant in this context.\nTRIM_SPACE (B): TRIM_SPACE is a file format option typically related to cleaning data\nduring the loading process by removing leading or trailing whitespace from fields. It has\nno impact on the overall file format (CSV, JSON, etc.) used when unloading data.\nSKIP_HEADER (D): SKIP_HEADER is again related to the loading operation. When\nloading from a file with a header row, this option allows you to skip that row. It does not\ncontrol the format of the data when it's unloaded.\nIn summary, to create a CSV or JSON file using the unloading functionality in Snowflake,\nyou must use the FILE_EXTENSION file format option to tell Snowflake to generate the\nfiles in that specific format. The other options deal with aspects of data loading, or\nmanipulating the contents of loaded strings and not with specifying the target output\nfile format during unloading.\nSupporting Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on COPY INTO (Unloading Data):\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/copy-into-location.html - Review the\nexamples that show FILE_FORMAT being used and how it relates to the created files in\nthe stage.\nSnowflake Documentation on File Formats: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/create-file-format.html - While this focuses on CREATE FILE FORMAT, it\nexplains parameters applicable in unloading scenarios, particularly regarding file\nextensions. Review the TYPE = CSV | JSON | AVRO | ORC | PARQUET | XML portion of\nthis documentation."
