                "explanation": "The correct answer is D, Named file format. Here's why:\nSnowflake recommends using a named file format when unloading similarly-formatted\ndata on a regular basis because it promotes efficiency, reusability, and maintainability. A\nnamed file format is a Snowflake object that encapsulates the specifications for reading\nor writing data files, including file type (CSV, JSON, etc.), field delimiters, compression\nmethods, and other format-specific options.By defining these specifications once in a named file format, you avoid repeatedly\nspecifying the same options in each unload command. This significantly simplifies the\nunload process and reduces the risk of errors caused by inconsistent formatting. When\nunloading data regularly, consistency is crucial. Using a named file format ensures that\nthe output files adhere to the same standard format each time, facilitating downstream\nprocessing and analysis.\nMoreover, named file formats enhance code reusability. Instead of embedding file\nformat options directly within the unload commands, you simply reference the named\nfile format. This modular approach makes it easier to update the formatting\nspecifications without modifying multiple unload commands. It also allows for easy\nstandardization across multiple data pipelines. If the underlying data structure or format\nchanges, you only need to update the named file format definition, and all unload\noperations using that format will automatically adapt.\nStreams (A) are for tracking data changes in tables, and Tasks (B) are for automating\nscheduled operations. Storage integrations (C) are used for secure access to external\ncloud storage locations and while crucial for unloading data to an external stage, they\ndon't define the data's format. Therefore, while a storage integration allows Snowflake\nto securely write to a specific S3 bucket, it does not specify that the data be written as\nCSV with a specific delimiter. Only the named file format will correctly handle that type\nof specification. The named file format is therefore the primary recommended method.\nFor further research, refer to the Snowflake documentation:\nCREATE FILE FORMAT\nUNLOAD DATA"
