                "explanation": "The correct parameters for differentiating between empty strings and NULL values\nduring data unloading in Snowflake are C. FIELD_OPTIONALLY_ENCLOSED_BY and D.\nEMPTY_FIELD_AS_NULL. These parameters provide the necessary control over how\ndata is represented in the unloaded files.\nFIELD_OPTIONALLY_ENCLOSED_BY specifies a character (like double quotes) to\nenclose field values. This is crucial because it allows Snowflake to clearly distinguish\nbetween an actual empty string \"\" which will be enclosed in the designated characters\nversus a field that should be interpreted as NULL. If no character encloses the value it is\neither a null or has a value that is being unloaded.\nEMPTY_FIELD_AS_NULL, when set to TRUE, instructs Snowflake to interpret any empty\nfield (one without enclosing characters) as a NULL value during the unloading process.\nWhen not set to true, an empty field will be unloaded as an empty string, unless\nspecified otherwise. This ensures that truly missing data is not mistaken for empty\nstrings and that nulls are handled as they are intended in the data warehouse.\nBy combining these two parameters, you maintain the integrity of the data during export.\nEmpty strings become actual empty string values while fields that contain no value are\naccurately unloaded as NULL.Let's see why the others are wrong: ESCAPE_UNENCLOSED_FIELD (A) specifies an\nescape character, while it helps to correctly handle characters in data, it does not\nexplicitly help with differentiation between NULL and empty strings.\nREPLACE_INVALID_CHARACTERS (B) replaces characters that are not valid in a\nspecified format and does not handle the case of differentiating between NULL and\nempty strings. SKIP_BLANK_LINES (E) will skip blank lines in the unloaded files and\ndoes not directly differentiate between empty strings and null values.\nHere are links for further research:\nSnowflake Documentation on Unloading Data: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/copy-into-location.html\nSpecifically, review the FORMAT option within COPY INTO <location>:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/copy-into-location.html#formatoptions-format_name"
