                "explanation": "The error \"Max LOB size (16777216) exceeded\" indicates that Snowflake encountered a single JSON value\nwithin the input file that exceeded its internal maximum size limit for a Large Object (LOB), which is\napproximately 16MB. This typically happens when loading large, nested JSON structures directly into a\nVARIANT column.\nOption A, compressing the file, won't solve the problem. Compression reduces file size but doesn't alter the\nsize of individual JSON objects parsed by Snowflake. The same overly large JSON value will still trigger the\nerror after decompression during the load process.\nOption B, splitting the file, is partially helpful but doesn't address the root cause. While smaller files are\ngenerally good practice for parallel processing, the oversized JSON value within any of those files will still\nresult in the same error. Splitting will only distribute the occurrence of the error, not eliminate it.\nOption C, using a larger warehouse, will not resolve the LOB size limitation. Warehouse size affects\ncomputational resources, not the maximum size of a single JSON object that Snowflake can process. The LOB\nsize is a system limitation independent of warehouse resources.\nOption D, setting STRIP_OUTER_ARRAY=TRUE, is the most likely solution because it addresses the structure\nof the concatenated JSON documents. Concatenated JSON files are often formatted as a single large JSON\narray where each element within the array represents a JSON document. Without\nSTRIP_OUTER_ARRAY=TRUE, Snowflake attempts to load the entire concatenated JSON file as one giant\nJSON document (and array) into a single VARIANT column. Each element in that array will become a single\nLOB value within Snowflake and if the array is small, all its content might be inserted into a single LOB\nsurpassing its size limit. Setting STRIP_OUTER_ARRAY=TRUE instructs Snowflake to treat each JSON\ndocument within the outermost array as a separate row in the target table. This effectively parses each\nindividual JSON document as a smaller, manageable LOB, circumventing the size limitation. If the error is\nspecifically about a single large object within a JSON document (and not the entire document) this will not\nsolve the problem, but from the question context, the problem is the entire concatenated set is considered\none JSON object.\nTherefore, STRIP_OUTER_ARRAY=TRUE is the correct approach to resolve the error and load the data\nsuccessfully. It modifies how Snowflake interprets the concatenated JSON, enabling proper parsing and\ningestion of the data without exceeding LOB size limits.\nReference:\nSnowflake COPY INTO command"
