                  "D": "Truncate the target table and reload the files.",
                  "E": "Use the ALTER TABLE...REFRESH command"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A",
                  "C"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is AC. Here's why:\nWhen loading data from stages into Snowflake tables, Snowflake tracks file metadata\n(e.g., file name, size, last modified time) to prevent duplicate loading. This metadata has\nan expiration period. After this period, Snowflake might not recognize the files as new,\nleading to potential issues.\nA. Set the LOAD_UNCERTAIN_FILES option to TRUE: The LOAD_UNCERTAIN_FILES\noption is explicitly designed for scenarios where files in a stage might have been\nmodified or where the metadata is no longer certain. Setting this option to TRUE allows\nSnowflake to consider these files again during a COPY command, even if their metadata\nsuggests they might have already been loaded. This is crucial when dealing with expired\nfile metadata, instructing Snowflake to bypass its usual checks and re-evaluate the files.\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/copy-into-table.html#copy-optionscopyoptions\nC. Set the FORCE parameter to TRUE: The FORCE parameter, when used with the COPY\ncommand, bypasses the data loading history and loads all files in the specified stageregardless of whether they've been loaded before. This overrides Snowflake's file\nmetadata tracking and ensures that the files are processed, effectively circumventing\nthe issue of expired metadata. It forces Snowflake to load the data anew.\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/copy-into-table.html#general-usagenotes\nWhy other options are incorrect:\nB. Remove the files from the stage and reload them: Removing and reloading the files\nwon't necessarily solve the problem if Snowflake still retains the expired metadata.\nWhile a new file instance might be created, Snowflake could potentially still recognize it\n(based on its contents or previous metadata) if the expiration handling hasn't been\nproperly addressed.\nD. Truncate the target table and reload the files: Truncating the table ensures that the\ntable is empty. However, it does not change how the COPY command works when\nreading files from the stage. Without addressing the metadata expiry, the COPY\ncommand may still skip some files.\nE. Use the ALTER TABLE...REFRESH command: This command is used to refresh the\nmetadata of a table, typically after DDL operations. It doesn't directly address the issue\nof expired file metadata in a stage, and is unrelated to how COPY command operates."
              }
            ]
          }
        },
