                },
                "answer": [
                  "B",
                  "D",
                  "E"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is B, D, and E: JSON, Avro, and Parquet. These are file formats that Snowflake natively\nsupports for loading semi-structured data. JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a widely used, humanreadable text-based format for representing data objects, making it ideal for handling nested structures. Avro\nis a row-oriented data serialization framework often used in Apache Hadoop, offering efficient data\ncompression and schema evolution capabilities. Parquet, also columnar in nature, excels at storage efficiency\nand fast query performance, especially suitable for analytical workloads. Snowflake's ability to ingest these\nformats directly allows for simplified data loading without complex transformations. Formats like TSV (Tab\nSeparated Values), PDF, and JPEG are not designed for storing or querying semi-structured data. TSV is\nsuitable for tabular data, PDF for documents, and JPEG for images, requiring preprocessing if incorporated\ninto a data pipeline. Snowflake's documentation explicitly lists JSON, Avro, and Parquet as the main\nsupported formats for semi-structured data ingestion.\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/data-types-semistructuredhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/data-load-considerations"
              },
              {
                "id": 469,
                "question": "Which semi-structured data formats can be loaded into Snowflake with a COPY command? (Choose two.)\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "CSV",
                  "B": "EDI",
                  "C": "HTML",
                  "D": "ORC",
                  "E": "XML"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "D",
                  "E"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. ORC and E. XML. Snowflake's COPY command is designed to load data from various\nsources, and it specifically supports semi-structured data formats like ORC and XML. ORC (Optimized Row\nColumnar) is a columnar storage format optimized for Hadoop and is often used in data lake environments.\nSnowflake can ingest ORC files directly, leveraging their columnar nature for efficient data processing. XML\n(Extensible Markup Language) is a hierarchical markup language commonly used for data serialization.\nSnowflake can parse XML documents and extract data into relational tables or variants. CSV and EDI are not\nconsidered semi-structured formats that are directly processed with a COPY command. CSV is a delimiterseparated file considered structured and loaded as a file and not semi structured. EDI or Electronic Data\nInterchange is not a data format for data loading in snowflake. HTML is a markup language for web content\nand not supported as data file format in snowflake. Snowflake treats these formats as structured data using\nfile format parameters and a staging.\nFor further information, consult the official Snowflake documentation on supported data file\ntypes:https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/copy-into-table.html#requiredparametershttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-load-transform.html#supported-file-formats"
              },
              {
                "id": 556,
                "question": "While loading data from a JSON file, what enables the removal of the outer array structure from the file and loads\nthe records into separate table rows?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "SKIP_BYTE_ORDER_MARK",
                  "B": "STRIP_NULL_VALUE",
                  "C": "STRIP_OUTER_ARRAY",
                  "D": "STRIP_OUTER_ELEMENT"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "C"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is C. STRIP_OUTER_ARRAY. Snowflake's COPY command, used for loading data from\nexternal files, offers options to handle various file structures. When dealing with JSON files containing a toplevel array of JSON objects, without STRIP_OUTER_ARRAY the entire array would be treated as a single row,\nrather than creating multiple rows from the individual objects. The STRIP_OUTER_ARRAY parameter\ninstructs Snowflake to bypass this outer array structure, processing each object within the array as a\nseparate row to be inserted into the target table. This parameter enables a direct mapping of the individual\nJSON objects' key-value pairs to corresponding columns in the table, based on column names or defined\nmapping. Options A, B and D are used for different file handling requirements. SKIP_BYTE_ORDER_MARK is\nused to ignore leading byte order marks, helpful when dealing with encoding issues. STRIP_NULL_VALUE is\nnot a valid option for the COPY command in Snowflake; there is no option to remove NULL values during load.\nOption D, STRIP_OUTER_ELEMENT is also not a valid COPY option in Snowflake. Therefore, only the\nSTRIP_OUTER_ARRAY option directly addresses the need to process individual elements within a JSON array\nas separate table rows. Without it, all array elements would be loaded into a single row, often into a variant\ncolumn. Understanding how to handle the outer array structure of a JSON document is crucial when working\nwith semi-structured data in Snowflake.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on COPY command options: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/copy-into-table.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Loading JSON Data: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/guides/snowflake-dataloading-transform.html"
              },
              {
                "id": 640,
                "question": "A user has semi-structured data to load into Snowflake but is not sure what types of operations will need to be\nperformed on the data.\nBased on this situation, what type of column does Snowflake recommend be used?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "ARRAY",
                  "B": "OBJECT",
                  "C": "TEXT",
                  "D": "VARIANT"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "D"
