                ],
                "explanation": "The statement is True. Snowflake's Web Interface (UI) provides a flexible worksheet environment where each\nworksheet operates independently. This independence extends to session-specific configurations. Users can\nconfigure a different role, database, schema, and virtual warehouse for each worksheet they have open. This\nis enabled through the worksheet's context menu, where users can select from available roles, databases,\nschemas, and virtual warehouses. Each worksheet establishes its own connection and context, allowing for\nsimultaneous work with different data sets, user permissions, and computational resources. These\nconfigurations apply solely to the individual worksheet session and don't affect other worksheets or the\nuser's overall environment. This granular control promotes efficient resource utilization, enables secure\naccess to different data environments, and facilitates multi-tasking within the Snowflake platform. Moreover,\nit helps to prevent errors caused by unintended modifications to a different context. The ability to switch\ncontexts per worksheet enhances user efficiency, allowing developers to work within specific projects or\nenvironments without switching out of the interface. The independent context management is crucial for\ncollaborative development, where users might require different access levels or work on different parts of adatabase.\nFor more information, refer to Snowflake's official documentation on:\nWorksheets in the Snowflake Web Interface: This page details how worksheets operate in the Snowflake Web\nUI, covering features like context switching.\nManaging Sessions: This section of the documentation provides a broader overview of managing sessions,\nwhich is related to the worksheet's session-specific settings.\nRoles: This section provides information on role based access control, highlighting the importance of\nswitching roles based on access needs."
              },
