                "explanation": "The correct answer is B, SYSADMIN. Here's why:\nSnowflake's role-based access control (RBAC) model emphasizes the principle of least privilege.\nACCOUNTADMIN is the most powerful role in Snowflake, essentially a superuser. Using it for routine tasks\nlike database creation violates this principle. While ACCOUNTADMIN could create databases, it's not best\npractice.\nSECURITYADMIN manages security-related configurations. Although they can manage grants, they are not\nprimarily responsible for the operational creation of databases. Similarly, USERADMIN is responsible for user\nand role management, not database administration.\nSYSADMIN, on the other hand, is designed for general system administration tasks. Creating and managing\ndatabases falls squarely within the responsibilities of a system administrator. The SYSADMIN role has the\nCREATE DATABASE privilege granted to it by default. Therefore, using SYSADMIN for database creation\nallows for segregation of duties and reduces the risk associated with using the ACCOUNTADMIN role\nunnecessarily. Best practices dictate minimizing the use of the ACCOUNTADMIN role to only those tasks that\nabsolutely require it. This ensures a more secure and auditable environment.\nFurthermore, using SYSADMIN allows for easier delegation of database creation responsibilities to team\nmembers without granting them excessive privileges. This promotes a more structured and securemanagement of the Snowflake environment. The deliberate separation of duties implemented through the\nSnowflake RBAC design allows businesses to adhere to audit, regulatory, and governance standards.\nSnowflake Documentation on SecuritySnowflake Documentation on Access Control"
