                "explanation": "The correct answer is CD (SECURITYADMIN and USERADMIN). Snowflake recommends against directly using\nACCOUNTADMIN for creating custom roles due to its all-encompassing privileges. Instead, delegating\nspecific administrative tasks to SECURITYADMIN and USERADMIN aligns with the principle of least privilege,\nenhancing security and auditability.\nSECURITYADMIN is responsible for managing security-related configurations, including creating and\nmanaging roles. This role has the necessary privileges to grant or revoke roles to other roles and users, thus\ncontrolling access to Snowflake resources.\nUSERADMIN focuses on user and role management, specifically creating, modifying, and managing users and\nroles within the system. This role allows for the separation of duties, preventing users responsible for security\nfrom also having full control over data and resources.\nUsing these roles for custom role creation isolates these responsibilities and offers a more granular control\nover administrative tasks compared to ACCOUNTADMIN, which possesses the highest level of privileges in\nthe system. Using ACCOUNTADMIN for role creation would grant excessive power to individuals or groups,\nincreasing the potential impact of security breaches or configuration errors. ORGADMIN is used for account\nmanagement across the entire Snowflake organization, and SYSADMIN has system-wide privileges related to\ndata and warehouse administration, not role management. Delegating these functions to SECURITYADMIN\nand USERADMIN minimizes the risk associated with the inherent power of ACCOUNTADMIN. This delegation\nalso helps in adhering to compliance requirements that mandate segregation of duties. The practice is to\ncreate custom roles with the required permissions and then grant these roles to users or other roles.\nFurther reading and confirmation of this best practice can be found in the Snowflake documentation:\nUnderstanding System Roles\nAccess Control in Snowflake"
