                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. The role that dropped the custom role. In Snowflake, object ownership is\nhierarchical and tied to roles. When a role that owns objects (like tables) is dropped, the ownership of those\nobjects is transferred, not to a higher-level administrative role like ACCOUNTADMIN or SYSADMIN, but rather\nto the role that performed the drop operation. This behavior is designed for accountability and control. The\nrole executing the DROP ROLE command effectively becomes the new owner of the objects previously\nowned by the dropped role. The tables won't become orphaned or standalone; Snowflake ensures that\nownership is always assigned to a role. This process maintains referential integrity and prevents a situation\nwhere objects exist without a designated owner. This is unlike certain systems where object deletion or role\nremoval may result in orphaned resources. The change of ownership is a direct consequence of the drop\noperation, giving the role dropping the custom role the control to maintain the tables.\nHere are some authoritative links for further research:\nSnowflake Documentation on Role-Based Access Control: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/security-access-control-overview\nSnowflake Documentation on DROP ROLE: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/drop-role\nSnowflake Documentation on Object Ownership: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/grantownership (While this link pertains to granting ownership, it explains the overall concept of ownership)"
              },
