                  "C": "Ownership depends on the type of object",
                  "D": "The role used to create the object"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D, \"The role used to create the object.\" Here's a detailed justification:\nIn Snowflake's role-based access control (RBAC) model, object ownership is a crucial aspect of security and\nprivilege management. When an object is created (e.g., a table, view, database), the role that was active at the\ntime of creation becomes the owner of that object. This role inherently possesses all privileges on the object,\nincluding the ability to grant those privileges to other roles.\nOption A, \"The user who created the object,\" is incorrect. Snowflake's access control revolves around roles,\nnot individual users. A user must be associated with a role to perform any actions within Snowflake. The user's\nidentity is secondary to the role they are using.\nOption B, \"The SYSADMIN role,\" is also incorrect. While the SYSADMIN role holds significant power within a\nSnowflake account and can manage various aspects of the system, it doesn't automatically become the owner\nof every object created. If the SYSADMIN role is active during object creation, then SYSADMIN becomes the\nowner. However, other roles might be used to create the object.\nOption C, \"Ownership depends on the type of object,\" is misleading. While different object types have\ndifferent privileges associated with them, the fundamental principle of role-based ownership remains\nconsistent across all object types. The role used during creation determines the owner, irrespective of the\nobject's type.\nThe significance of role-based ownership lies in its flexibility and control. By assigning ownership to roles,\nSnowflake allows for separation of duties and centralized management of privileges. For example, a\nDATA_LOADER role could be used to create and manage tables for loading data, without granting individual\nusers direct ownership.\nTherefore, the role actively used when the object is created becomes the owner and initially inherits allapplicable privileges on that object, which it can then delegate as needed.Snowflake Documentation on\nAccess Control: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-access-control.htmlSnowflake\nDocumentation on Roles: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-access-control-configure.html"
              },
