                "explanation": "The correct answer is B (Role-Based Access Control - RBAC) and E (Discretionary Access Control - DAC).\nSnowflake employs a hybrid approach to access control combining these two models.\nRole-Based Access Control (RBAC): Snowflake primarily uses RBAC. This involves assigning privileges to\nroles, and then assigning those roles to users. RBAC simplifies access management by grouping permissions\nbased on job function. A user inherits the combined privileges of all roles assigned to them. For instance, a\n\"Data Analyst\" role might have SELECT privileges on certain tables, and assigning this role to a user grants\nthem that access. This approach promotes consistency and reduces the risk of assigning incorrect privileges\nto individual users. RBAC is a widely adopted and crucial security practice in cloud\nenvironments.https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-access-control-overview.html#role-basedaccess-control\nDiscretionary Access Control (DAC): DAC means that object owners (typically the user who created the\nobject) have significant control over who can access their objects. In Snowflake, the owner of a database,schema, or table, for example, can grant specific privileges (like SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE) to other roles or\nusers. This discretionary aspect allows for fine-grained control over data access at the individual object level.\nAlthough Snowflake emphasizes RBAC, DAC provides the flexibility for owners to customize access policies.\nWhy the other options are incorrect:\nA. Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML): SAML is an XML-based standard for exchanging\nauthentication and authorization data between security domains. It's used for Single Sign-On (SSO), not for\nthe internal access control model.\nC. Identity Access Management (IAM): IAM is a broad term for managing digital identities and their access\nrights. RBAC and DAC are specific models within an IAM framework. While IAM is relevant, it's too general to\nbe a specific component of Snowflake's access control model.\nD. Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD): CRUD is a set of database operations; not an access control\nmodel. Permissions to perform CRUD operations are managed through RBAC and DAC in Snowflake.\nF. Mandatory Access Control (MAC): MAC is a highly restrictive access control model where a central\nauthority determines access policies. It is not a feature of Snowflake.\nIn summary, Snowflake leverages RBAC for streamlined and consistent access management based on roles,\nand DAC for object owners to customize access at a more granular level. This combination provides a robust\nand flexible security posture."
