                "explanation": "The correct answer is C. SYSTEM$ALLOWLIST. Here's a detailed justification:\nSnowsight, Snowflake's web interface, can be accessed through various network configurations.\nTo enhance security, Snowflake provides mechanisms to control which networks can reach\nSnowsight, often involving proxies. The function responsible for this is SYSTEM$ALLOWLIST. This\nfunction enables administrators to define a list of allowed network locations, specifically IPaddresses or ranges. When configured, any attempt to access Snowsight from an IP address not\non the allowlist will be blocked, effectively protecting it by restricting access to authorized\nnetworks. SYSTEM$ALLOWLIST does not provide direct proxy information itself; instead, it uses\nthe provided IP addresses to create an allowlist, implicitly integrating with proxy infrastructure\nthrough address configurations.\nOptions A, B, and D are incorrect. SYSTEM$GET_TAG is used to retrieve tags associated with\nSnowflake objects, not for network security. SYSTEM$GET_PRIVATELINK is designed to return\ninformation about Snowflake Private Link configurations, relating to direct connections that\nbypass public internet. Similarly, SYSTEM$AUTHORIZE_PRIVATELINK grants access to Private\nLink resources, not controlling general proxy access. They do not address the core security need\nof limiting Snowsight access via allowlisting, as achieved by SYSTEM$ALLOWLIST. Allowlisting\nusing IP addresses or CIDR ranges is a foundational security practice in cloud environments for\ncontrolling access from known and trusted networks, thus making SYSTEM$ALLOWLIST the best\nchoice for proxy integration and Snowsight protection.\nFor further research, refer to the official Snowflake documentation on network policies:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/network-policies.html and Snowsight security:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-snowsight-access.html. These resources detail how\nnetwork policies, specifically through the use of allow lists, function within the Snowflake\nplatform."
