                  "B": "Read access",
                  "C": "Write access",
                  "D": "Full access"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is A. No access. In Snowflake, and indeed in most secure cloud environments,\na fundamental principle is the concept of \"least privilege.\" This means that users and roles should\nonly have the minimum necessary access to perform their tasks. When a securable object, such as\na database, table, view, or user, is created, it is not accessible by default. This ensures that data\nand resources are protected and that access must be explicitly granted. If a default level of\naccess, such as 'Read,' 'Write,' or 'Full' were granted by default, it would introduce a significant\nsecurity risk as it would open the possibility of unintended or malicious access to sensitive data.\nSnowflake utilizes a role-based access control (RBAC) model, where privileges are granted to\nroles, and roles are assigned to users. Therefore, to access a newly created object, a user must\nhave a role with the necessary privileges granted to that role for that specific object, typically\nusing the GRANT command. Only after explicit permissions are granted does a user or role gain\naccess, reflecting the system's secure-by-default approach. This is essential for maintaining data\nintegrity, confidentiality, and compliance in cloud environments.\nHere are authoritative links for further research:\nSnowflake Documentation - Access Control in Snowflake: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/security-access-control-overview\nSnowflake Documentation - Overview of Privileges: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/grant-privilege\nSnowflake Documentation - Securable Objects: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/security-access-control-securable-objects"
