                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. REVOKE ROLE.\nHere's a detailed justification:\nIn Snowflake's role-based access control (RBAC) model, roles are granted to other roles or users\nto manage permissions effectively. To remove a role from another role or user, the REVOKE ROLE\ncommand is used. This command explicitly revokes the granted privilege, meaning the target user\nor role will no longer inherit the permissions associated with the revoked role. The syntax\ngenerally follows: REVOKE ROLE <role_name> FROM ROLE | USER <role_name | user_name>.\nThis action is critical for maintaining the principle of least privilege and ensuring that users and\nroles have only the necessary permissions to perform their duties.\nOption A, ALTER ROLE, is used to modify the properties of a role, such as renaming it, but not for\nrevoking roles from users or other roles. Option C, USE ROLE, is used to switch the active role in\nthe current session and does not affect role grants. Option D, USE SECONDARY ROLES, is used to\nspecify roles used for authorization and does not have the functionality to revoke access. Hence,\nthe only command that handles the removal of a role from a user or another role is REVOKE ROLE.\nThe REVOKE ROLE command is a fundamental component of maintaining a secure and wellmanaged Snowflake environment by controlling the access and permissions of users and roles.\nWithout the ability to revoke role privileges, organizations would face difficulties in implementing\nand enforcing their security policies.\nFor further research, refer to Snowflake's official documentation:\nREVOKE ROLE: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/revoke-role\nOverview of Access Control: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-access-controloverview\nRole-Based Access Control: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-access-controlrbac"
