                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. Use a managed access schema. Here's the justification:\nIn Snowflake, managed access schemas provide a critical layer of control over object\nprivilege management. Unlike regular schemas, where the object owner (typically the\nuser who created it) can freely grant privileges to other users, managed access schemas\ncentralize this control. When a managed access schema is created, only the schema\nowner or users granted the MANAGE GRANTS privilege on the schema can grant or\nrevoke privileges on objects within that schema. This means that even if a user creates\nan object within a managed access schema, they do not automatically gain the right to\ngrant privileges on it to others. This behavior aligns perfectly with the requirement of\nrestricting other users' ability to grant privileges on objects within the schema.\nOption A, using a regular schema, does not enforce the desired restriction. The object\nowner in a regular schema retains the ability to grant privileges. Option C, a transient\nschema, is about data persistence and has no impact on privilege management. Option D,\nsetting the Default_DDL_Collation parameter, pertains to data sorting and collation, notuser privileges.\nTherefore, to limit privilege-granting capabilities to specific users, employing a managed\naccess schema is the recommended approach in Snowflake. This model enhances\nsecurity and provides granular control over access to schema objects.\nFor further research, refer to the official Snowflake documentation on managed access\nschemas:\nSnowflake Managed Access Schemas: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/security-access-control-managed-access-schema"
