                  "E": "Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML)"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A",
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "Snowflake employs two primary security models for managing access control:\nDiscretionary Access Control (DAC) and Role-Based Access Control (RBAC). DAC grants\nobject owners control over who can access their objects (e.g., tables, views). Owners can\ndirectly grant privileges to other users or roles. RBAC, conversely, manages access by\nassigning privileges to roles, and then granting those roles to users. This simplifies\naccess management, especially in large organizations. Users inherit privileges assigned\nto the roles they are granted. While Snowflake uses Role-Based Access Control as the\ncore security model, it leverages Discretionary Access Control in its object ownership\nand grant mechanisms, making both models vital in Snowflake's security architecture.\nIdentity Access Management (IAM), which handles user identities and authentication, is\nnot directly a security model for access control in this context, nor is Mandatory Access\nControl, which is rarely used in commercial Cloud Databases. Security Assertion Markup\nLanguage (SAML) is used for federated authentication, not access control directly.\nTherefore, options A (Discretionary Access Control) and D (Role-Based Access Control)\nare the correct choices.\nSnowflake Security OverviewSnowflake Access Control"
