                "explanation": "The SnowPro Core exam question asks about the types of objects for which Snowflake's Information Schema\nprovides storage information. The correct answer is B. Databases and C. Internal stages.\nThe Information Schema in Snowflake is a set of system-defined views that contain metadata about\nSnowflake objects. This metadata includes information about storage, size, and creation details, amongst\nother things. The Information Schema specifically tracks details about database objects and their underlying\nstorage.\nDatabases are containers for schemas, tables, views, and other objects. The Information Schema provides\ndetails about the size of databases, creation timestamps, and other metadata useful for management and\nmonitoring.\nInternal stages, used to store data files within Snowflake's internal storage, also have storage information\ntracked by the Information Schema. This includes information about the files stored in the stage, their sizes,\nand access details. This allows users to monitor storage utilization within Snowflake and manage their data\nmore effectively.\nUsers and Resource Monitors, while important Snowflake constructs, don't directly relate to storage in the\nway that databases and stages do. User information is primarily about access and permissions, and is stored in\ndifferent metadata views. Resource monitors track credit usage, not the physical storage footprint of data.\nPipes are related to data ingestion, but the Information Schema provides details about the storage of the data\ningested, not the Pipes themselves.\nTherefore, databases and internal stages are the two object types for which the Information Schema directly\nprovides storage information, making options B and C the correct answer. This aligns with Snowflake's\ndocumentation detailing the purpose and scope of the Information Schema.\nReference links:\nSnowflake Information Schema: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/info-schema.html\nSnowflake Stages: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-load-internal-tutorial.html"
