                "explanation": "Let's break down why options C and D are the correct choices regarding the differences between Snowflake's\nAccount Usage views and Information Schema views.\nOption C: \"Account usage views contain dropped objects but information schema views do not.\" This is\naccurate. Account Usage views, designed for historical analysis and auditing, retain information about objects\neven after they've been dropped. This allows administrators to track object lifecycles and understand past\nactivity. Information Schema views, on the other hand, are essentially \"live\" representations of the current\nstate of a database or schema. Once an object is dropped, it's no longer reflected in the Information Schema.\nOption D: \"Data retention for account usage views is 1 year but is 7 days to 6 months for information\nschema views, depending on the view.\" This highlights a crucial difference. Account Usage views maintain\ndata for a considerably longer period (1 year), providing a comprehensive historical record for analysis.\nInformation Schema views have a much shorter data retention period, ranging from 7 days to 6 months,\nbecause they focus on providing a real-time snapshot of the database's structure. This shorter retentionperiod is appropriate as their main purpose is metadata access rather than long-term historical analysis.\nWhy other options are incorrect:\nOption A: \"No active warehouse is needed to query account usage views but one is needed to query\ninformation schema views.\" While Account Usage views do operate differently, you do need an active\nwarehouse to query both types of views. The distinction lies more in how they are structured and their purpose\nrather than the requirement for an active warehouse.\nOption B: \"Account usage views do not contain data about tables but information schema views do.\" This is\nfalse. Account Usage views do contain information about tables, including creation times, drop times, and\nusage statistics.\nOption E: \"Information schema views are read-only but account usage views are not.\" Both Information\nSchema views and Account Usage views are read-only. You cannot modify the data through these views.\nIn summary, the key difference between these two view types comes down to their intended use: Account\nUsage views for historical tracking and auditing with long retention; and Information Schema views for a live,\nup-to-date reflection of database structures and metadata with shorter retention.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Account Usage: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/account-usage\nSnowflake Documentation on Information Schema: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/infoschema"
