                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. ACCESS_HISTORY.\nThe ACCESS_HISTORY view in Snowflake is specifically designed to provide information\nabout object access operations, including read and write operations performed on\ntables. This view tracks which users or roles have accessed specific tables and how they\naccessed them (e.g., through a query, load, or DML operation). It enables security\nauditing and data lineage analysis. By examining the ACCESS_HISTORY, you can\nidentify which queries, tasks, or users have read data from a table or written data to it,\nmaking it a valuable tool for understanding data access patterns and identifying\npotential security vulnerabilities or compliance issues.\nCOPY_HISTORY, on the other hand, is designed to track the history of data loading\noperations using the COPY command. QUERY_HISTORY provides a record of all queries\nexecuted in the system but doesn't directly link to specific object access.\nTASK_HISTORY pertains to the execution history of scheduled tasks. While these views\nprovide valuable information, they do not granularly track table-level read/write\noperations like ACCESS_HISTORY does. For example, QUERY_HISTORY will show the\nSQL query itself, but not specifically break down which tables were read from versus\nwritten to within that query. ACCESS_HISTORY serves this purpose specifically.\nTherefore, to track read and write operations performed on a table, ACCESS_HISTORY is\nthe most appropriate view.\nSnowflake ACCESS_HISTORY View Documentation"
