                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. Use dynamic data masking.\nHere's why:\nDynamic data masking in Snowflake allows for the selective obscuring of data at query runtime, based on the\nrole or privileges of the user executing the query. This precisely addresses the requirement of making\nsensitive data invisible to end users while revealing a partial view to functional managers.\nOption A, data encryption, secures data at rest and in transit, preventing unauthorized access to the\nunderlying data files, but it doesn't control what is displayed to different users when querying the data.\nOption C, secure materialized views, could potentially provide different views of the data. However, managing\nnumerous views for various access levels can be complex and might not be the most efficient solution for this\nscenario. Furthermore, if the underlying table has sensitive data visible to managers via the materialized view,\nit could be indirectly revealed to end-users.\nOption D, revoking all roles, would prevent both managers and end-users from accessing the data, which\ncontradicts the requirement for managers to have partial visibility.\nDynamic data masking is the most suitable solution because it allows administrators to define policies that\nspecify how data should be masked based on the user's context, ensuring granular control over data visibility\nwithout altering the underlying data itself. This approach maintains data integrity while meeting the specific\naccess requirements of different user groups. It allows for a centralized management of masking policies,\nsimplifying administration compared to creating multiple views.https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/data-masking-introhttps://www.snowflake.com/blog/dynamic-data-masking-snowflake-security/"
              },
              {
                "id": 216,
                "question": "A company needs to allow some users to see Personally Identifiable Information (PII) while limiting other users\nfrom seeing the full value of the PII.\nWhich Snowflake feature will support this?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Row access policies",
                  "B": "Data masking policies",
                  "C": "Data encryption",
                  "D": "Role based access control"
