                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is B, Data Masking Policies. Here's why:\nData masking policies in Snowflake are specifically designed to control the visibility of sensitive data like PII\nat the column level. They allow you to define rules that redact, substitute, or obfuscate data based on the role\nor user accessing it. This directly addresses the requirement of allowing some users to see the full PII while\nlimiting others. For example, you can create a masking policy that shows the full Social Security Number\n(SSN) to HR personnel but masks it for customer service representatives, displaying only the last four digits.\nRow access policies (A) restrict access to rows in a table based on user attributes or roles. While useful for\noverall data access control, they don't provide the granularity to selectively mask portions of a column's data.\nThey would either allow a user to see the entire row (including the PII) or prevent them from seeing it\naltogether.\nData encryption (C) protects data at rest and in transit but doesn't control user-level access to specific parts\nof the data. Even with encrypted data, users with appropriate permissions would still see the full, unmaskedPII. Encryption protects against unauthorized access to data at a storage level, not selective display of data to\nauthorized users.\nRole-based access control (RBAC) (D) is fundamental for managing permissions in Snowflake, but it's not\ngranular enough to achieve the required data masking. RBAC grants or revokes access to objects like tables\nand views, but it doesn't inherently allow for selective masking of data within a column based on the user's\nrole. It's a component of data security, but it's not the feature providing granular control over PII visibility as\nrequested in the question. It may be combined with data masking policies for comprehensive data security.\nTherefore, data masking policies provide the targeted solution for selectively displaying PII based on user\nroles, enabling a company to comply with data privacy regulations while maintaining operational efficiency.\nFurther research:\nSnowflake Data Masking: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-masking.html\nSnowflake Row Access Policies: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/row-access-policies.html"
              },
