                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. Dynamic Data Masking and C. External Tokenization. These two features directly\ncontribute to column-level security in Snowflake. Dynamic Data Masking allows for the obfuscation of\nsensitive data in columns based on user roles or contexts. This means that users with insufficient privileges\nwill see masked or altered data, ensuring that sensitive information remains protected without altering the\nunderlying stored data. For example, a user might see only the last four digits of a credit card number instead\nof the full value. External Tokenization, on the other hand, involves replacing sensitive data with non-sensitive,\nmeaningless tokens. The actual sensitive data is stored in an external vault. When the tokenized data is\naccessed in Snowflake, it retrieves the sensitive data from the external vault only when required and if the\nuser has the necessary permission. This separation of sensitive data from Snowflake further enhances\nsecurity.\nContinuous Data Protection (CDP), while important for data resilience, is not directly related to column-level\nsecurity. CDP focuses on data backup and recovery. Key pair authentication concerns user authentication and\nis not about controlling access to specific columns. Row access policies, although important for data security,\nfocus on filtering rows, not columns. Therefore, options A, D, and E are incorrect. The combination of dynamic\ndata masking and external tokenization ensures that even if a user can access a column, they may not be able\nto see the true data, thus fulfilling the primary purpose of column-level security. These mechanisms offer\ncrucial safeguards against unauthorized data exposure, making them essential features of Snowflake's\nsecurity arsenal.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Dynamic Data Masking: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/securitycolumn-masking\nSnowflake Documentation on External Tokenization: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/guides-security-exttokenization"
