                "explanation": "The correct answer is B because secure views in Snowflake provide an added layer of data protection by\nconcealing the underlying query logic from users who are granted access to the view. Unlike standard views,\nwhere users can view the definition, secure views prevent this exposure. This is critical for protecting sensitive\nbusiness logic or transformation rules embedded in the view's query. Also, Snowflake employs internal\noptimizations specifically for secure views, meaning they don't necessarily execute in the same way as\nstandard views. These optimizations are usually focused on performance and security, though these\noptimizations are opaque to the user. Options A, C, and D are incorrect. Secure views do not leverage a\nspecific SECURE_ACCESS property for user access (A); access is still controlled via standard privileges. Data\nreplication and enhanced encryption (C) are not specific to secure views but are part of overall Snowflake\ndata protection features. And while secure views can be used in conjunction with features like masking and\nrow-level policies, they do not introduce those features themselves (D). Secure views primarily serve to\nprotect the view's logic and allow for Snowflake specific optimizations.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Secure Views: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/views-secure.html"
