                },
                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is B: A tag can have only one masking policy for each data type. Let's break down why.\nTags in Snowflake are metadata labels used to categorize and manage data. Masking policies, on the other\nhand, are used to control how data is displayed based on user roles or other criteria, enhancing data security\nand privacy. While tags can be associated with masking policies, the relationship isn't direct. A tag isn't the\nobject being masked, but rather, it's a tool to help manage and identify objects that might need masking. The\nlimitation lies in how masking policies are applied.\nMasking policies are associated directly with a column of a table, view, or external table. You can't directly\nattach a masking policy to a tag. However, a tag can help you locate which columns to apply a policy to. For\nexample, you might have a tag called \"PII\" that's applied to columns containing personally identifiable\ninformation. Then, you'd create a masking policy and assign it to each column identified by that tag. The\nessential part is that a single column can have, at most, one masking policy applied at a time, specific to each\ndata type it holds. This is to avoid conflicting masking rules and ensures data integrity and predictability.\nTherefore, if you have multiple columns tagged with \"PII\" that hold different data types (e.g., string and date),\nyou could apply a single string masking policy to all relevant string type columns, and a date masking policy\nto date columns, but a given string column can have only one string policy. This reinforces the correctness of\noption B: A tag can have only one masking policy for each data type. Options A, C, and D are incorrect because\na tag is a metadata object and it does not directly inherit or influence the masking policy application\nconstraints. There is no relationship between dropping a tag and its association with a policy. Also, a given\ncolumn (not tag) can only have one masking policy of a given type applied, and that is regardless of any tags.\nHere are some resources for further information:\nSnowflake documentation on Tagging: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/object-tagging\nSnowflake documentation on Masking Policies: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-columnmasking"
