                "explanation": "Secure views in Snowflake are specifically designed to enhance data security and control access\nto underlying data, addressing two primary concerns. Option C is correct because secure views\nenable hiding sensitive data from users who do not have explicit permissions to access it. Instead\nof exposing the entire underlying table, a secure view can expose only specific columns or\naggregated data, effectively masking confidential information. This functionality is crucial for\nenforcing data privacy and complying with regulations. Option E is also correct because secure\nviews hide their own definition, i.e., the SQL code defining the view, from users who don't have the\nnecessary privileges. This prevents unauthorized users from seeing how the data is derived or\npotentially exploiting the underlying logic. Standard views, in contrast, expose their definition,\nmaking them less secure. Option A is incorrect because encryption in transit is handled through\nseparate TLS encryption and not related to secure views. Option B is incorrect because secure\nviews, if not created with care, can actually reduce performance compared to a standard view if\nthe logic or security filters add overhead. Option D is not correct either, secure views do not\ninherently improve query performance; they might even introduce overhead due to additional\nsecurity checks.\nFor further details about secure views in Snowflake, refer to the official\ndocumentation:https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/views-secure.htmlThis resource\nelaborates on the purpose, characteristics, and security aspects of secure views, further\nsolidifying the justification for options C and E being the correct answers."
