                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. External tokenization. Column-level security in Snowflake primarily\nfocuses on controlling access to sensitive data within specific columns of a table. This is achieved\nthrough masking and tokenization techniques. External tokenization, in this context, refers to the\nprocess of replacing sensitive data values with non-sensitive substitutes (tokens) via an external\ntokenization service before the data is ingested into Snowflake. This method allows for the full\nfunctionality of Snowflake while keeping the sensitive information secure outside the platform.\nRole access policies (A), while crucial for overall security, manage access at the object level (e.g.,\ntables, schemas) rather than at the granular column level. Network policies (B) control network\ntraffic and do not directly impact the visibility of data within a column. Internal tokenization (C)\nwould involve Snowflake handling the tokenization process, but this is not a primary feature of\ncolumn-level security; instead, Snowflake integrates with external services for this purpose. By\nusing external tokenization, organizations can adhere to compliance requirements, maintain the\nutility of the data for various operations, and safeguard sensitive information from unauthorized\naccess. In essence, column-level security, particularly with external tokenization, adds a crucial\nlayer of data protection by providing fine-grained control over sensitive fields within a dataset.\nThis approach offers a balanced solution for data security and usability.\nAuthoritative Link:Snowflake Column-Level Security"
              },
              {
