                "question": "What does a masking policy consist of in Snowflake?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "A single data type, with one or more conditions, and one or more masking functions",
                  "B": "A single data type, with only one condition, and only one masking function",
                  "C": "Multiple data types, with only one condition, and one or more masking functions",
                  "D": "Multiple data types, with one or more conditions, and one or more masking functions"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A"
                ],
                "explanation": "Here's a detailed justification for why option A is the correct answer regarding the structure of a\nmasking policy in Snowflake:\nA masking policy in Snowflake is a crucial component of data security, designed to dynamically\nredact or transform sensitive data based on specific conditions. The fundamental structure of a\npolicy is built around a single data type to ensure consistent application. This means a single\npolicy targets columns containing data of a particular type (e.g., STRING, NUMBER, DATE),\nallowing Snowflake to handle various data transformations effectively.\nWithin a masking policy definition, you'll find one or more conditions that dictate when the\nmasking function(s) should be applied. These conditions leverage the SQL expression language\nwithin Snowflake, often making use of functions and logical operators to evaluate the context of\nthe query. This context can include the role of the user, or the value of other columns within the\ntable. The versatility in expressing these conditions is important for nuanced data masking\nscenarios.\nFurthermore, a masking policy uses one or more masking functions to actually perform the data\ntransformation. These functions take the column's original value as input and produce a modified\nversion. Snowflake supports both built-in masking functions (e.g., mask, mask_email,\nmask_number) and custom functions (user-defined functions or UDFs), giving considerable\nflexibility in the type of masking being applied. Therefore, masking policies are flexible and are\napplicable to different scenarios. Because a masking policy must be applied to data with a specific\ntype, the flexibility provided via multiple conditions and functions offers the user the options they\nneed.\nThe other options can be ruled out. Options B is wrong because masking policies support multiple\nconditions, not a single one, to cater to different data redaction requirements. Option C and D are\nincorrect as masking policies are designed for a single data type to maintain consistency and\npredictability of the transformation process.\nIn summary, option A accurately defines a Snowflake masking policy as being for a single data\ntype, containing one or more conditions, and using one or more masking functions, providing\ngranular control over how sensitive data is protected.\nHere are authoritative links for further research:\nSnowflake Documentation - Masking Policies: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/create-masking-policy\nSnowflake Blog - Introducing Data Masking in Snowflake:\nhttps://www.snowflake.com/blog/introducing-data-masking-in-snowflake/"
              },
              {
                "id": 929,
                "question": "In which hierarchy is tag inheritance possible?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Organization » Account » Role",
                  "B": "Account » User » Schema",
                  "C": "Database » View » Column",
                  "D": "Schema » Table » Column"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. Schema » Table » Column. Tag inheritance in Snowflake follows a\nhierarchical pattern where tags applied at a higher level in the hierarchy are inherited by objects\nnested within it. This concept is similar to inheritance patterns in object-oriented programming.\nTags applied to a schema are inherited by all tables within that schema. Subsequently, tags on a\ntable are inherited by all columns within the table. This inheritance mechanism streamlines tag\nmanagement and ensures consistency, minimizing repetitive tag assignments. Option A,\n\"Organization » Account » Role,\" is incorrect. While organization and accounts are hierarchical,roles don’t inherit tags from them; roles have their own taggable properties. Option B, \"Account »\nUser » Schema,\" is also incorrect as users don’t inherit tags from accounts, and schemas, while\nrelated to accounts, are not nested within users. Option C, \"Database » View » Column,\" is\npartially correct in that views can inherit from databases; however, the view level does not\ndirectly have inheritance to columns, since views are defined with an underlying structure. Tag\ninheritance is fundamental for enforcing consistent metadata management and security policies\nacross Snowflake objects. It allows for streamlined data governance through centralized tag\nassignments. For further exploration, refer to the official Snowflake documentation on Tagging:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/ddl-tag.html."
