                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. Data classification. Here's why:\nData classification in Snowflake involves tagging columns with metadata that indicates\nthe type of data they hold (e.g., PII, sensitive, financial). While not directly logging reads\nof column data itself, it's a critical foundation for auditing read access. By understanding\nwhat kind of data resides in a column (through its classification), organizations can\ndetermine if an access attempt should be logged and audited. This allows for the\ncreation of granular policies that might trigger logging only for sensitive data reads.\nAccess History, while crucial for auditing, primarily tracks who accessed what object,\nbut doesn't inherently indicate specific column-level data read. Column-level security,\nthrough features like masking and row-level security, controls access to data,\npreventing reads, not necessarily logging them. Object dependencies show how objects\nare linked, not how access to the data within them is handled.\nTherefore, data classification is the key first step. Once sensitive columns are identified\nvia classification, downstream auditing processes can then use this metadata to track\nand log when those classified columns are accessed through user queries. It acts as a\ntrigger for additional audit logging setup. The actual logging of reads isn't a direct\nfunction of classification, but classification facilitates and enables it.\nFor further exploration, refer to the official Snowflake documentation on data\ngovernance and classification:\nSnowflake Data Governance Overview: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/datagovernance-overview\nSnowflake Data Classification: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/dataclassification\nSnowflake Access History: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/infoschema/access_history"
