                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is A. It selectively masks plain text data. Conditional masking in\nSnowflake operates by applying a masking policy to a column, but it only applies the\nmasking transformation if a specified condition is met. Unlike static masking, which\nalways transforms data, conditional masking provides more granular control, allowing\nyou to hide sensitive information only when necessary. The condition is typically based\non values within another column or other context-dependent criteria, making it\ncontextual rather than blindly applying a mask. This flexibility allows you to reveal some\ndata while simultaneously concealing other data within the same column based on other\ndata elements. Option B is incorrect as while multiple columns can be masked using\nmultiple policies, conditional masking itself operates on a single column based on the\ncondition. Option C is incorrect, as while masking policies can indeed mask all values in a\ncolumn, the conditional aspect is what distinguishes it; masking policies applied without\nconditions do not constitute conditional masking. Option D is incorrect because\nconditional masking is not dependent on a related column for its functionality (the\ncondition for masking may rely on other column values, but the result is masking the\ntargeted plain text column). It focuses on selectively masking the content of a single\ncolumn based on a predefined condition, leading to granular and efficient data\nprotection. In essence, conditional masking in Snowflake targets plain text within a\nspecific column, applying transformations based on a condition.\nFurther Research:\nSnowflake Documentation on Data Masking: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/data-masking\nSnowflake Blog on Conditional Masking: [Search for Snowflake blog posts on\nConditional Masking policies.]"
