                "explanation": "Here's a detailed justification for why option D, Tag-based masking policies, is thecorrect answer in the context of column-level security in Snowflake:\nColumn-level security in Snowflake focuses on controlling access to specific columns\nwithin a table. It aims to protect sensitive data at a granular level. Tag-based masking\npolicies offer a powerful way to achieve this. Masking policies determine how data is\ndisplayed to users based on their roles or privileges. These policies can redact, hash, or\npartially mask data.\nTag-based masking policies are particularly advantageous because they allow you to\ndynamically apply masking rules based on metadata associated with the columns.\nSnowflake tags are metadata objects that can be associated with various Snowflake\nobjects, including columns. These tags can represent data classification, sensitivity\nlevels, or other relevant attributes.\nBy associating a masking policy with a tag, and then applying that tag to columns\ncontaining sensitive data, you create a dynamic and scalable security framework. When\na user queries a column with an applied masking policy, Snowflake evaluates the tag\nassociated with that column and applies the corresponding masking rule based on the\nuser's roles and the conditions defined in the policy.\nOption A, Object tagging, is the mechanism by which we associate tags with columns,\nand therefore important, but it doesn't directly enforce column-level security. It's a\nsupporting feature.\nOption B, Data classification, is related to understanding the sensitivity of data, but it\ndoesn't directly implement access control. It's more of a prerequisite to using columnlevel security effectively.\nOption C, External tokenization, is another data protection technique, but typically\napplies at a different level and is not inherently integrated into Snowflake's columnlevel security features. While it can complement masking policies, it is not the primary\nsupported feature.\nTherefore, Tag-based masking policies leverage the power of object tagging to\nimplement dynamic and scalable column-level security in Snowflake. The other options\nprovide supporting context or are alternative data protection techniques.\nFor more information, refer to the official Snowflake documentation:\nMasking Policies: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-column-maskingpolicies\nObject Tagging: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/object-tagging"
