              {
                "id": 1233,
                "question": "A network policy set at which level will override all other network policies?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Account",
                  "B": "User",
                  "C": "Security integration",
                  "D": "Database"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The provided answer, B (User), is incorrect. The correct answer is A (Account).\nNetwork policies in Snowflake are hierarchical. An account-level network policy has the\nhighest precedence and overrides any other network policies defined at lower levels,\nsuch as user or security integration levels. This design ensures that the strictest security\nrules, enforced at the account level, are always applied. Network policies control access\nto Snowflake based on IP addresses, allowing you to restrict access to your Snowflake\naccount. When a user attempts to connect, Snowflake checks network policies in a\nspecific order. If an account-level policy is in place, its rules are evaluated first. If a userlevel network policy is also set, the account-level policy still takes precedence. This\nmeans that even if a user is explicitly allowed access by a user-level policy, but the\naccount-level policy blocks their IP address, access will be denied. Similarly, policies\nattached to security integrations also adhere to this hierarchy. Account-level policies\nact as the overarching gatekeeper, ensuring consistent security enforcement across the\nentire Snowflake environment. Lower-level policies, if they exist, are effective only if\nthey do not conflict with the account-level policy. This prioritization simplifies security\nmanagement, as central administrators can define overarching rules that apply to allusers and integrations within the Snowflake account. This behavior is well documented\nin Snowflake's official documentation.\nRefer to the official Snowflake documentation on Network Policies for detailed\ninformation and examples: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/networkpolicies.html"
              },
