                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. OPERATE. Here's why:\nIn Snowflake, controlling the operational state of a warehouse (like resuming it from a suspended state)\nrequires the OPERATE privilege. This privilege grants a role the authority to perform actions that directly\naffect the execution of queries and the utilization of compute resources associated with a warehouse. It is\ndistinct from simply using the warehouse for queries (USAGE) or monitoring its activity (MONITOR).\nSpecifically, when a warehouse is suspended and its auto-resume feature is disabled, someone with the\nOPERATE privilege is needed to explicitly bring it back online. The USAGE privilege only allows querying\nwithin the warehouse, but not altering its state. MONITOR allows you to check the warehouse's status but not\nchange it. MODIFY, on the other hand, is used to alter configuration aspects of the warehouse. Resuming a\nwarehouse is a direct operational task.\nThe OPERATE privilege is fundamental for managing warehouse lifecycle and is essential for scenarios where\nmanual intervention is necessary to bring a warehouse out of a suspended state. This contrasts with autoresume which removes that need but is not relevant in this question, where we are focusing specifically on a\nscenario when auto-resume is off.\nTherefore, the OPERATE privilege is the most appropriate privilege for a role required to resume a suspended\nwarehouse when auto-resume is not active.\nFor further information and clarification, refer to the official Snowflake documentation on warehouse\nprivileges: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/grant-privilege.html and\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/alter-warehouse.html."
