                "explanation": "The correct answer is C: \"Privileges are only inherited by the direct parent role in the hierarchy.\"\nSnowflake's role-based access control (RBAC) model implements a hierarchical structure, where\nroles can be granted to other roles, forming a tree-like structure. When a role is granted to\nanother, the granting role becomes the parent and the granted role becomes the child within thehierarchy. In Snowflake, privileges granted to a role are not automatically inherited by all roles\nhigher up the hierarchy (Option A). Instead, inheritance flows upwards, one level at a time. This\nmeans a child role inherits the privileges of its direct parent role. It also does not mean that a role\ninherits privileges from roles at the same level (Option B) or that the parent role inherits the\nchild's privileges (Option D). This explicit, parent-to-child, upward inheritance is crucial for\nmaintaining granular control and limiting privilege escalation. This design also ensures a\nstraightforward understanding of permission assignments. If a user needs more access, the\nsolution is to assign the user one of the parent roles which inherit all of the lower level roles\npermissions. This approach promotes the Principle of Least Privilege by enabling specific\npermissions only where they are required. This helps maintain a more secure and manageable\nsystem. The design avoids unintended access granting that can be prone to issues if it were to\nwork at different levels and flows.\nFor further research, refer to the official Snowflake documentation on Role-Based Access\nControl:https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-access-control-overview and\nspecifically on inheritance https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-access-controlrbac.html#role-hierarchy-and-privilege-inheritance"
