                "explanation": "The SYSTEM$GLOBAL_ACCOUNT_SET_PARAMETER function in Snowflake is designed to\nmanage account-level parameters, which directly impacts the overall behavior and configuration\nof the entire Snowflake account. Access to this sensitive function is therefore highly restricted.\nThe ORGADMIN role, introduced to manage organizational-level configurations, is the designated\nrole granted access to this function by default. This aligns with the principle of least privilege,\ngranting the necessary administrative control to manage the global aspects of the Snowflake\naccount. While ACCOUNTADMIN has ultimate control over an account, it does not directly interact\nwith this specific global configuration function; instead, ACCOUNTADMIN typically delegates\nthese responsibilities through the ORGADMIN role. Roles like SECURITYADMIN and SYSADMIN\nfocus on different aspects of account management, such as security and database administration,\nrespectively, and do not have default access to this organization-level configuration setting\nfunction. Granting access to this function to non-ORGADMIN roles needs explicit permission\nthrough grants. The ORGADMIN role's responsibility for organizational-level parameters is adesign consideration to streamline the administrative hierarchy and to promote better separation\nof concerns for security and operational tasks. Therefore, ORGADMIN is the only role with default\naccess to the SYSTEM$GLOBAL_ACCOUNT_SET_PARAMETER function.\nAuthoritative Link: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/functions/system_global_account_set_parameter (This link directly relates to the\nfunction and its permission)https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-access-controloverview (This link provides information about role based access controls.)"
