                  "C": "SELECT",
                  "D": "USAGE"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D, USAGE. Accessing a file URL from an external stage in Snowflake\nrequires the minimum permission of USAGE on the stage object itself. This is because the USAGE\nprivilege grants the ability to utilize the stage for operations such as referencing files within its\nlocation. It doesn't directly grant permission to the underlying cloud storage; Snowflake manages\naccess to that via its own integrations with your cloud provider (e.g., IAM roles for AWS S3). The\npermissions required on the actual cloud storage are separate.While READ permission might seem relevant for reading file content, it's not applicable at the\nSnowflake object level. Similarly, MODIFY is for altering the stage's properties or its location, and\nSELECT is relevant to accessing data inside Snowflake tables not external files. To put simply,\nUSAGE allows Snowflake to know which storage location it can access.\nThink of the external stage as a doorway to your external cloud storage. The USAGE privilege\ngives the Snowflake user the key to that door to look through it and see the files available but\ndoesn't grant access to the files themselves. Instead, Snowflake handles access to files via\nintegration between Snowflake and your cloud provider's IAM tools. You don't need a READ\npermission on the stage to get to the files; you need USAGE to make the stage available in the\nfirst place. You must also have appropriate permissions defined for the cloud storage bucket that\nthe stage points to.\nSnowflake's access control model is designed so that privilege on objects is distinct from actual\naccess to the underlying files. The principle of least privilege is central, requiring only USAGE for\nSnowflake's internal awareness of a stage for referencing its file location.\nAuthoritative Links for Further Research:\nSnowflake Documentation on External Stages and Permissions:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/create-stage.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Access Control: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/security-access-control.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Stage Privileges: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/grant-privilege.html"
