                "id": 958,
                "question": "Who can grant object privileges in a regular schema?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Object owner",
                  "B": "Schema owner",
                  "C": "Database owner",
                  "D": "SYSADMIN"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is A, the object owner. In Snowflake, the principle of least privilege is central\nto security. Object privileges, such as SELECT or INSERT on a table, are fundamentally controlled\nby the entity that owns that specific object. This owner, typically the user or role that created the\nobject, has inherent rights, including the authority to grant privileges to other users or roles.\nWhile schema owners can create objects within a schema, they do not automatically control the\nprivileges on those objects. Database owners also lack the authority to directly manage object\nprivileges contained within its schemas. The SYSADMIN role, though powerful, does not dictate\ngranular object-level permissions; instead, it manages broader system-level configurations. The\nobject owner holds the power to delegate access and maintain fine-grained control over their\nowned entities, ensuring data security and compliance. Therefore, only the object owner can grant\nobject privileges in a regular schema. The Schema and Database owners can revoke privileges\nfrom the objects owned by others, in turn, object owners can grant these privileges back.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation - Access Control: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/securityaccess-control-overview\nSnowflake Documentation - Privileges: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/grantprivilege\nSnowflake Documentation - Object Ownership: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/security-access-control-manage-ownership"
