                "question": "Which privilege is required on a virtual warehouse to abort any existing executing queries?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "USAGE",
                  "B": "OPERATE",
                  "C": "MODIFY",
                  "D": "MONITOR"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct privilege for aborting existing executing queries on a Snowflake virtual\nwarehouse is OPERATE. The OPERATE privilege grants the ability to perform actions\nthat directly affect the operational state of the warehouse, and this includes stopping\nrunning queries. While USAGE grants the ability to use the warehouse, it doesn't confer\ncontrol over its operational activities. The MODIFY privilege allows changes to the\nwarehouse's configuration, such as sizing or auto-suspend parameters, but it doesn't\naffect currently running queries. Similarly, MONITOR provides visibility into the\nwarehouse's performance and usage but not the ability to actively control its operations,\nlike aborting queries.\nIn essence, OPERATE is the specific privilege designated for tasks that require active\nmanagement and intervention of an active virtual warehouse, including terminating or\naborting currently running SQL statements. The ability to stop a query is an operation\nimpacting an already operating resource, necessitating the OPERATE privilege. The\nother privileges listed do not grant the required operational control to perform such\nactions. This segregation of privileges ensures a more granular security model where\nusers have access only to the actions they need to perform, adhering to the principle of\nleast privilege. A user only with USAGE can execute queries but can't manage them. A\nuser with MODIFY can change the overall properties but not the ongoing operations. A\nuser with MONITOR can only look at what is happening but not interfere.\nFurther details about these privileges and their uses are found in the official Snowflake\ndocumentation. Specifically, refer to the section explaining warehouse privileges for acomprehensive understanding of each privilege's scope and its impact on virtual\nwarehouse functionalities. Understanding these privileges is crucial for implementing\nsecure access control within a Snowflake environment.\nAuthoritative Link:\nSnowflake Documentation - Warehouse Privileges"
