                "explanation": "The correct answer is A. OPERATE. In Snowflake, managing the operational state of a\npipe object—specifically pausing or resuming it—requires the OPERATE privilege. This\nprivilege grants the user the authority to control the active execution of the pipe. Pipes\nin Snowflake are used for continuous data loading, and their operational state directly\naffects data ingestion. READ and SELECT privileges are related to accessing data within\ntables or views, not controlling the pipe itself. USAGE is typically associated with the\nability to reference or utilize a schema or database, and it doesn't grant the necessary\ncontrol over pipe operations. Think of OPERATE as the \"on/off\" switch for the pipe's data\ningestion process. Without the OPERATE privilege, a user can neither pause nor resume\nthe pipe's functionality, even if they can see or read the data. This privilege is distinct\nfrom other privileges related to data access or database structure. It focuses\nspecifically on the management of pipe objects. The OPERATE privilege ensures that\nonly authorized personnel can affect the continuous data load process. Snowflake's\naccess control system is designed to provide granular permissions, enhancing security\nand data governance. Therefore, the privilege required to pause or resume pipes is\nexplicitly the OPERATE privilege on the pipe object itself.\nFurther research:\nSnowflake documentation on Pipe privileges: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/grant-privilege.html#pipe-privileges\nSnowflake documentation on Access control: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/security-access-control.html"
