                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. DELETE. The OVERWRITE option within an INSERT statement in\nSnowflake functions by implicitly deleting existing data in the target table before\ninserting new records. This action requires the role executing the INSERT statement to\npossess the DELETE privilege on that specific table. The OVERWRITE functionality\nessentially combines a DELETE operation followed by an INSERT. Without the DELETE\nprivilege, the operation would fail, as Snowflake's security model rigorously enforces\naccess control. While TRUNCATE can also remove all data from a table, it requires a\nseparate privilege and is not the mechanism implicitly used by INSERT ... OVERWRITE.\nUPDATE is for modifying existing data and SELECT is for reading, neither of which are\ndirectly related to the data removal aspect of INSERT ... OVERWRITE. Snowflake's\ndocumentation explicitly highlights the necessity of the DELETE privilege for this\noperation. This design ensures controlled data manipulation and adheres to the principle\nof least privilege. Therefore, the DELETE privilege is the most suitable and accurateanswer.https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/insert.htmlhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-accesscontrol-privileges.html"
