                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is C. REFERENCE_USAGE. When sharing data via secure views in\nSnowflake, you're not directly sharing the underlying tables. Instead, you're sharing a\nview, which depends on the underlying data within the referenced databases. To allow\nthe consumer account to access and use this view, even though it is a secure view, they\nneed access not just to the view, but also the databases where the referenced tables\nreside. Granting REFERENCE_USAGE on each of these databases to the share ensures\nthe consumer account's view can resolve the data dependencies. If they were to only\nreceive USAGE on these databases, they wouldn't have the permission to reference\nspecific objects within the database (such as a table accessed by the view). They can use\nit as a container for the secure view. The REFERENCES privilege would be relevant to\nallow creation of views or secure views, not in the consumer account and not to access\nthe view's references, or usage within the share. READ is not a valid privilege for\ngranting access to database container in Snowflake. Essentially, REFERENCE_USAGE\ngrants the ability for shared objects to resolve database objects within the share's\ndatabase(s), a crucial element for secure view functionality. Without\nREFERENCE_USAGE , the consumer account would not be able to successfully query\nthe shared secure view.\nFor further reading, consult Snowflake's official documentation:\nSharing Secure Views\nPrivileges on Databases\nUnderstanding Data Sharing"
