                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is A. GRANT and E. CREATE USER. Let's break down why:\nIn Snowflake, managing users involves controlling their access and permissions. The\nGRANT privilege plays a crucial role by allowing a user to grant specific privileges to\nother users. This includes the ability to assign roles which, in turn, control access to\nobjects and resources. Without the GRANT privilege on a role that grants necessary\npermissions, a user cannot effectively manage other users' access.\nThe CREATE USER privilege, as its name suggests, is absolutely necessary to create\nnew user accounts in Snowflake. This privilege is granted to roles, which, when assignedto a user, enables them to create new users within the Snowflake account.\nThe other options are incorrect because they lack the inherent ability to manage users.\nSELECT is a privilege for querying data, MODIFY is for changing data within tables, and\nOWNERSHIP allows for full control of a specific object, not necessarily management of\nusers. While ownership might influence access, it's not a primary privilege for user\ncreation and general management. User management requires controlling access and\ncreating new identities, the GRANT and CREATE USER privileges are therefore\nessential. Therefore, a user holding both the GRANT and CREATE USER privileges (or\nheld by a role that grants them these privileges) is able to create and manage users in a\nSnowflake account.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation - GRANT Privileges: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/grant-privilege.html\nSnowflake Documentation - CREATE USER: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/create-user.html\nSnowflake Documentation - Overview of Access Control:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-access-control-overview.html"
