                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is C. OWNERSHIP. In Snowflake, the OWNERSHIP privilege is unique\nand critical because it dictates complete control over an object. Unlike other privileges\nlike MONITOR or OPERATE, OWNERSHIP grants the ability to perform all actions on the\nobject, including granting further privileges, altering its structure, and even dropping it.\nImportantly, once OWNERSHIP is granted from one role to another, it cannot be revoked\ndirectly. The recipient of OWNERSHIP then has full authority over the object, effectively\nbecoming the new owner. The previous owner no longer has inherent control unless the\nnew owner explicitly grants privileges back. This behavior ensures that there is a single,\ndefinitive owner responsible for an object's lifecycle and security. Revoking ownership\nrequires transferring it to another role, rather than directly removing it. The inability to\nrevoke ownership directly is a design choice in Snowflake to maintain a clear chain of\ncontrol and prevent accidental loss of access to critical objects. Therefore, while other\nprivileges can be granted and revoked, the permanency of OWNERSHIP transfer\ndistinguishes it from the rest, making it the correct answer in this context. This\nfundamental design ensures the integrity and security of Snowflake object\nmanagement.Further Research:\nSnowflake Documentation on Access Control: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/security-access-control-overview\nSnowflake Documentation on Ownership and Privileges:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/grant-privilege"
