                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is C and D. When sharing data in Snowflake, providers grant access\nto consumers through shares. Shares themselves don't directly grant access; instead,\nthey reference objects within the provider's Snowflake account. To enable a consumer to\naccess data in a share, a provider needs to grant specific privileges. Firstly, SELECT\nprivileges (option C) are essential. Consumers need to have the ability to query the data,\nthus requiring SELECT privileges on the specific tables included in the share. This is the\nfundamental permission for data retrieval. Secondly, USAGE privileges (option D) on the\ndatabase and schema are crucial. USAGE privileges on the container objects (database\nand schema) are prerequisites to accessing objects within them. Without USAGE on the\ndatabase and schema, the consumer cannot even browse or see the tables being shared,\neven if they have SELECT privileges on the tables. Options A, B, and E are not correct.\nOption A, USAGE on tables, is not needed. Option B, MODIFY on the tables, is incorrect\nbecause sharing is a read-only operation for consumers. Option E, OPERATE, is not a\nvalid privilege applicable to databases or schemas in this context. Sharing is designed\nfor read-only access by consumers, ensuring the data owner maintains control over data\nmodification. This follows the principle of least privilege, granting only the necessary\npermissions for consumers to perform their operations which are to query and read the\nshared data. These permissions are crucial for consumers to be able to utilize the data\nprovided via the share.\nAuthoritative links for further research:\n1. Snowflake Documentation on Sharing Data: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/grant-privilege.html (Specifically the section on GRANT\n<privileges> TO SHARE)\n2. Snowflake Documentation on Data Sharing:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/data-sharing-intro.html\n3. Snowflake Documentation on Understanding Privileges:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-access-controloverview.html#privileges"
