                "explanation": "The correct answer is D: A user with a role that has been granted the OWNERSHIP\nprivilege on both the user and the network policy.\nTo activate a network policy for an individual user in Snowflake, you need the necessary\nprivileges to modify both the user and the network policy. The OWNERSHIP privilege is\nthe highest level of privilege and allows you to perform any action on the object,\nincluding altering its properties.\nSpecifically, you must have ownership of the user object because activating a network\npolicy for a user essentially modifies the user's properties to associate them with that\npolicy. You also need ownership of the network policy because applying the policy to a\nuser requires modifying the policy's configuration to associate it with the user. Without\nownership of both objects, you lack the necessary permissions to establish the link\nbetween the user and the policy.\nOption A is incorrect because ATTACH POLICY is a global privilege that applies to\nsession policies, not network policies and not necessarily to individual users. Option B is\nwrong because CREATE SESSION POLICY allows you to create session policies but does\nnot provide the rights to apply network policies to users. Option C is incorrect because\nCREATE NETWORK POLICY permits the creation of network policies, but it does not\ngrant the privileges to assign these policies to specific users. Only the OWNERSHIP\nprivilege on both the user and the network policy grants the complete authority required\nto make this association.\nFor further research, consult the official Snowflake documentation:\nNetwork Policies: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/network-policies.html\nAccess Control Privileges: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-accesscontrol-privileges.html\nOwnership Privilege: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/grantownership.html"
