ud provider’s region.\nThis is incorrect. As explained above, Snowflake uses multiple availability zones for redundancy and high\navailability. Using only a single availability zone would be a single point of failure, making the service\nvulnerable to outages.\nB. Snowflake data and services are available in a single cloud provider and a single region; the use of\nmultiple cloud providers is not supported. This is also incorrect. Snowflake is available on multiple cloud\nproviders (AWS, Azure, and Google Cloud). Furthermore, it supports multiple regions within each cloud\nprovider, allowing customers to choose the region closest to their data or users for performance and\ncompliance reasons.\nC. Snowflake can be deployed in a customer’s private cloud using the customer’s own compute and storage\nresources for Snowflake compute and storage. This is incorrect. Snowflake is a fully managed service and\noperates within the cloud providers' infrastructures that it supports (AWS, Azure, and Google Cloud). It does\nnot run on customers’ private clouds or infrastructure. The customer does not have control over the\nunderlying infrastructure of Snowflake.\nAuthoritative Links for Further Research:\nSnowflake Architecture: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/guides-overview-architecture - Provides an overview\nof Snowflake's architecture, including how it leverages cloud infrastructure.\nSnowflake Regions: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/admin-regions - Details where Snowflake is\navailable and the supported cloud providers and regions.\nSnowflake High Availability: Search Snowflake documentation for concepts related to high availability and\nfailure tolerance.These resources will offer a deep dive into the specifics of Snowflake's architecture and how\nit operates within cloud environments."
