                "explanation": "The correct answer is C: It is a hybrid of traditional shared-disk and shared-nothing database architectures.\nSnowflake's architecture distinctly separates storage and compute resources, a key characteristic of a hybrid\napproach. Unlike a shared-disk architecture where all compute nodes access the same storage directly,\nSnowflake utilizes a central storage layer (shared-disk in principle). However, this storage is not directly\naccessed by compute nodes; instead, it is accessed through a virtual layer. The compute nodes, organized into\nvirtual warehouses, operate independently from each other, representing a shared-nothing architecture. Each\nwarehouse has its own independent compute resources (memory, CPU). This separation allows for\nindependent scaling of compute and storage resources and minimizes resource contention. Data stored in the\ncentral storage layer is accessed by these independent virtual warehouses via caching, enabling them to\nperform computations without being tightly coupled. This decoupled design provides the benefits of both\narchitectural models: the centralized management and cost-effectiveness of shared disk, and the scalability\nand performance of shared-nothing. The decoupling of storage and compute is a foundational design principle\nin cloud-native systems.\nFurther Research:\nSnowflake Architecture\nShared-Disk vs Shared-Nothing Architectures\nCloud Computing Architecture"
