                "explanation": "The Cloud Services layer in Snowflake is responsible for managing the overall operation of the\nplatform, essentially acting as the \"brain\" behind the data storage and processing engines. User\nauthentication (D) is a core function of this layer, handling the verification of user credentials and\nauthorization to access Snowflake resources. This ensures only authorized individuals or\napplications can interact with the data. The Cloud Services layer also performs crucialinfrastructure management tasks, such as controlling virtual warehouse allocation, workload\nmanagement, and system-level monitoring. Infrastructure management (E) is therefore a critical\nactivity, coordinating the underlying resources to ensure smooth and efficient operation.\nData storage (A), while a fundamental component of Snowflake, is handled by the Storage layer,\nnot the Cloud Services layer. Dynamic data masking (B) is a feature that modifies data visibility\nbased on user roles and policies. While the rules for dynamic masking are configured through the\nCloud Services, the actual data transformation occurs in the Query Processing Layer. Partition\nscanning (C), the action of locating and retrieving relevant data partitions, is primarily associated\nwith the Query Processing layer, which uses metadata information from Cloud Services to\noptimize data access, not solely in Cloud Services. The Cloud Services layer is primarily focused\non management and control, not the direct manipulation or retrieval of data.\nFor more details on the Snowflake architecture and the specific roles of each layer, refer to the\nofficial Snowflake documentation: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/intro-keyconcepts.html#snowflake-architecture and https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/introconcepts.html."
              },
