                "answer": [
                  "A",
                  "E"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is A. Authentication and E. Query parsing and optimization. Snowflake's\narchitecture is built upon three distinct layers: the Cloud Services layer, the Query Processing\nlayer, and the Database Storage layer. The Cloud Services layer is the \"brain\" of Snowflake,\nresponsible for coordinating activities across the other layers.\nAuthentication is a core function of the Cloud Services layer. It handles user login, validatescredentials, and manages security aspects, ensuring that only authorized users can access the\nsystem. This is fundamental to any secure data platform. Similarly, query parsing and\noptimization occur within the Cloud Services layer. When a user submits a query, this layer\nanalyzes the query syntax, constructs an optimized execution plan, and determines the most\nefficient way to retrieve the requested data. This involves tasks such as converting the query into\na logical execution plan and choosing optimal access paths.\nOptions B, C, and D are handled by other layers. Access delegation is more closely associated with\nthe Query Processing layer, managing access at a granular level during query execution. Data\npruning and compression occur within the Database Storage layer, where data is physically stored\nand managed. Data pruning determines the relevant micro-partitions for a query and is executed\nduring the query processing phase, although it is closely related to how data is stored. Data\ncompression occurs upon writing data to the storage layer.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Architecture: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/intro-keyconcepts.html#snowflake-architecture\nSnowflake Documentation on Cloud Services Layer: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/intro-key-concepts.html#cloud-services-layer"
