                "id": 939,
                "question": "How does Snowflake describe its unique architecture?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "A single-cluster shared data architecture using a central data repository and massively parallel processing",
                  "B": "A multi-cluster shared data architecture using a central data repository and massively parallel processing",
                  "C": "A single-cluster shared nothing architecture using a siloed data repository and symmetric multiprocessing",
                  "D": "A multi-cluster shared nothing architecture using a siloed data repository and symmetric multiprocessing"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "Snowflake's architecture is accurately described as a multi-cluster shared data architecture\nusing a central data repository and massively parallel processing (MPP). This means that\nSnowflake utilizes multiple compute clusters, each capable of independent scaling and\nprocessing, to execute queries concurrently. All these clusters access a single, shared data\nrepository where the data is physically stored, eliminating the need for data copies across nodes.\nThis contrasts with \"shared nothing\" architectures where each node has its own isolated data\nstorage. The central repository facilitates data consistency and avoids the complexity of\nmanaging distributed data. Furthermore, Snowflake leverages massively parallel processing,\nwhich breaks down queries into smaller tasks that are distributed across the compute clusters for\nsimultaneous execution, leading to faster performance. This decoupling of compute and storage\nallows for independent scaling of resources, providing elasticity and cost optimization.\nSnowflake's architecture differs significantly from systems based on Symmetric Multiprocessing\n(SMP) which rely on a single machine for processing, thereby limiting scalability. You can find\nmore details about Snowflake's architecture in their official documentation:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/intro-key-concepts.html and\nhttps://www.snowflake.com/blog/snowflake-architecture-explained/. Additionally, explore\nresources related to cloud data warehousing and MPP architectures for more context."
