                "explanation": "The correct answers are A and E, reflecting key advantages of Snowflake's unique\narchitecture. Option A, \"The separation allows independent scaling of computing\nresources,\" is a fundamental benefit. Snowflake decouples compute (virtual\nwarehouses) from storage, allowing users to independently adjust the size or number of\nvirtual warehouses based on query workload without impacting the stored data. This\nelasticity ensures optimal performance and cost management as compute can scale up\nfor heavy workloads and down during idle periods. Option E, \"Compute can be scaled up\nor down without the requirement to add more storage,\" is another crucial aspect. As\ncompute resources are managed separately, scaling a virtual warehouse does not\nmandate an increase in storage. This is in contrast to traditional architectures, where\ncompute and storage were often tied together. Users can process larger datasets or\nexecute more complex queries by adding compute without incurring additional storage\ncosts.\nOption B is incorrect because while Snowflake does offer robust encryption, it's not\ninherently tied to the separation of compute and storage. Option C is incorrect because\nsemi-structured data conversion is a feature of Snowflake, not a direct consequence of\nthe compute-storage separation. Option D is incorrect because the separation\nspecifically aims for decoupled growth of storage and compute, not tight coupling. The\nability to independently scale compute and storage provides crucial flexibility, allowing\nusers to optimize resource usage based on specific needs and workloads while\nmaintaining the desired level of performance. This architecture is a hallmark of cloudnative data warehouses.\nFor further research, refer to the following resources:\nSnowflake Documentation: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/ (Specifically, explore\nsections on architecture and virtual warehouses)\nSnowflake Blog: https://www.snowflake.com/blog/ (Search for articles discussing the\nbenefits of the architecture)\nCloud Computing Concepts: Refer to general cloud architecture materials to understand\nthe decoupling of compute and storage, for example, AWS, Azure or GCP documentation\naround cloud data warehouses and architecture."
