                ],
                "explanation": "The statement is False. While it's common for the creating user to be granted ownership of a newly created\nobject in many systems, Snowflake's object ownership model is more nuanced. By default, when a user\ncreates a Snowflake object, the object is actually owned by the role that was active during the object\ncreation, not the user. This distinction is crucial because a user can have multiple roles, and the active role at\nthe time determines ownership. Therefore, if the user's active role does not have appropriate ownership\nprivileges, the user might not automatically own the object. This mechanism enforces the principle of least\nprivilege and enables better security and control in multi-user environments. The role that creates the object\ngets all privileges on that object, unless explicitly changed via a GRANT statement. Users may have the ability\nto create objects but if they are not using a role that has the relevant access, they will not automatically be\nthe owners. This concept differs from typical systems where the user is the default owner and underscores\nSnowflake's role-based access control.\nFor further reading on Snowflake's access control framework and how object ownership is managed, refer to\nthe official Snowflake documentation:\nOverview of Access Control\nUnderstanding Role-Based Access Control\nAccess Control Privileges"
