                  "B",
                  "C"
                ],
                "explanation": "Here's a detailed justification for why temporary and transient tables are the correct choices for reducing\ndata storage costs for short-lived tables in Snowflake:\nTemporary Tables:\nTemporary tables exist only within the session in which they were created and are automatically dropped at\nthe end of the session. This means that the data they contain is not persisted beyond the session, eliminating\nany long-term storage costs.\nSince temporary tables are session-specific, they provide data isolation and prevent conflicts between\ndifferent users or processes.\nThe immediate deletion of temporary tables at session end ensures automatic cleanup, reducing\nadministrative overhead associated with managing storage.\nTheir volatility makes them ideal for storing data needed only for the duration of a specific query or task.\nTransient Tables:\nTransient tables are similar to permanent tables but do not have a Fail-safe period. Fail-safe provides a\nhistorical data recovery period (typically 7 days) after Time Travel has expired. Without Fail-safe, the storage\ncosts associated with historical data versions are eliminated.\nTransient tables have a Time Travel period (up to 1 day for Enterprise Edition, and 0 days for Standard Edition),\nbut it's shorter than permanent tables (up to 90 days). A shorter Time Travel means less storage is consumed\nfor historical data.\nTransient tables offer a balance between data persistence and cost efficiency, suitable for data that needs to\npersist across sessions but doesn't require long-term recovery options.\nTransient tables are automatically dropped when the user account is deleted.\nWhy the other options are incorrect:\nPermanent Tables: Permanent tables are designed for long-term data storage. They have Fail-safe and Time\nTravel enabled, incurring higher storage costs.\nProvisional Tables: There's no \"Provisional Tables\" object type in Snowflake.\nLookup Tables: Lookup tables can be temporary, transient, or permanent, but are specifically designed for\ndata lookup purposes not as general-purpose short-lived tables, so while a lookup table could technically be\ntransient or temporary, it isn't a method of reducing storage costs specifically for short-lived tables.\nIn summary, temporary tables eliminate storage costs by only existing within a session, and transient tables\nreduce costs by foregoing Fail-safe and having a shorter Time Travel period compared to permanent tables.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Table Types: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tables-temporary.htmlSnowflake Documentation on Transient Tables: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tablestransient.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Permanent Tables: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tablespermanent.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Understanding Data Retention: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/data-availability.html"
