                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. Database and C. Schema. In Snowflake, a namespace uniquely identifies an object\nwithin the system. This identification is hierarchical and is structured using a multi-level approach. The top\nlevel of this hierarchy is the database, which serves as a logical container for schemas. Schemas, the next\nlevel down, are themselves containers for various database objects, such as tables, views, and procedures.Together, the database and schema act as a combined entity that provides a unique namespace where objects\nare stored and referenced. This layered structure ensures that object names are not only unique but also\nlogically grouped. Without the database and schema combination, object names could clash, particularly in\nscenarios where multiple users or applications access a single Snowflake account. This organization\npromotes clarity and efficient access control. Specifying both the database and schema in a qualified name\n(e.g., DATABASE.SCHEMA.OBJECT) guarantees that the intended object is located regardless of which role is\ncurrently active or other contextual settings. Therefore, only a combination of a database and a schema\nguarantees a unique namespace. Tables, virtual warehouses, and the account are not themselves parts of the\nobject namespace hierarchy.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation - Database, Schema, and Share Naming: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/name-resolution.html\nSnowflake Documentation - Understanding Databases and Schemas: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/databases-schemas.html"
