                "id": 741,
                "question": "Which statement describes Snowflake tables?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Snowflake tables are logical representations of underlying physical data.",
                  "B": "Snowflake tables are the physical instantiation of data loaded into Snowflake.",
                  "C": "Snowflake tables require that clustering keys be defined to perform optimally.",
                  "D": "Snowflake tables are owned by a user."
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is A: Snowflake tables are logical representations of underlying physical data.\nThis is because Snowflake employs a separation of compute and storage. The table definition you\nsee and interact with in Snowflake's SQL interface is a logical construct, defining the schema and\ndata types. However, the actual data is stored and managed separately in Snowflake's proprietary\ncloud storage layer.\nOption B is incorrect because tables are not the physical instantiation. Instead, they are\nreferences to the data stored elsewhere. Snowflake manages the physical storage of data and\nhow it's organized behind the scenes. You don't have direct control over or visibility into that\nphysical layer.\nOption C is incorrect because while clustering keys can improve query performance, they are not\nmandatory for a table to function optimally. You can create and use tables without ever defining a\nclustering key. Tables still operate perfectly well and can be queried without these keys, though\nsome queries might be slower.\nOption D is incorrect since tables are not owned by a user but a database or schema. Users have\nprivileges on tables, allowing them to access or modify data, but they don't \"own\" the table itself.\nIt's an object within the Snowflake account and not assigned to a specific user.\nThis separation between logical table structure and physical storage allows Snowflake to offer\nfeatures like time travel and zero-copy cloning. You can query old data or create cloned tables\nwithout impacting the original data because those logical table references point to different\nsnapshots of the physical data. This characteristic is a core tenet of modern cloud data\nwarehouses.\nFor further research on Snowflake's architecture and table structure, you can refer to\nSnowflake's official documentation:\nSnowflake Data Storage: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-storage.html\nUnderstanding Tables: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tables-intro.html\nClustering Keys: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tables-clustering-keys.html\nAccess Control and Privileges: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/security-accesscontrol.html"
