                "id": 839,
                "question": "Which Snowflake object does not consume any storage costs?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Secure view",
                  "B": "Materialized view",
                  "C": "Temporary table",
                  "D": "Transient table"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A"
                ],
                "explanation": "Here's a detailed explanation why the correct answer is A. Secure views in Snowflake, unlike\nother table-like objects, do not consume storage costs because they do not store any data.\nInstead, a secure view acts as a virtual table, dynamically querying and presenting data from its\nunderlying base tables each time it is accessed. This behavior is similar to a standard view but\nwith enhanced security features. Materialized views, however, do store precomputed results and\nthus incur storage costs for the replicated data. Temporary tables, created within a user session,\nalso take up storage, though they are automatically dropped at the end of the session and their\ncosts are typically temporary. Transient tables, while not intended for permanent storage like\nstandard tables, also consume storage; they lack the fail-safe protections of permanent tables,\nbut still use storage. The 'virtual' nature of secure views prevents them from storing persistent\ndata, making them cost-effective in terms of storage. The data accessed via secure views is\nalways up to date as queries fetch the latest version of the base data. For further details on\nsecure views and their behavior, refer to the official Snowflake documentation:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/views-secure.html,\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tables-temp-transient.html."
