              {
                "id": 1004,
                "question": "A tag object has been assigned to a table (TABLE_A) in a schema within a Snowflake database.\nWhich CREATE object statement will automatically assign the TABLE_A tag to a target object?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "CREATE TABLE LIKE TABLE_A;",
                  "B": "CREATE VIEW AS SELECT * FROM TABLE_A;",
                  "C": "CREATE TABLE AS SELECT * FROM TABLE_A;",
                  "D": "CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW AS SELECT * FROM TABLE_A;"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is A. CREATE TABLE LIKE TABLE_A;. This is because the CREATE\nTABLE LIKE statement in Snowflake is specifically designed to clone the structure and\ndefinition of an existing table, including its schema, columns, constraints, and\nimportantly, its tags. This inherent behavior of the LIKE clause ensures that the new\ntable automatically inherits any tags associated with the source table.\nOptions B, C, and D, while creating new objects based on the data or structure of\nTABLE_A, do not preserve the tags. CREATE VIEW, CREATE TABLE AS SELECT, and\nCREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW AS SELECT statements are focused on defining new\nobjects based on a query result set. They primarily copy the data and derived column\ninformation but not the underlying metadata like tags. Snowflake's tag propagation\nmechanism is explicitly designed to accompany object definitions rather than data\ncontent. Thus, a direct data copy operation does not bring the original table's tags to thenew object.\nIn essence, CREATE TABLE LIKE is the only command among the options designed for\nstructural copying and therefore will automatically inherit the tag in question. This is a\nkey feature of Snowflake for managing metadata and enabling data governance policies\nconsistently. For more information, refer to Snowflake's official documentation on\ncloning and object tags:\nSnowflake Documentation - CREATE TABLE LIKE\nSnowflake Documentation - Tagging Objects"
              },
              {
                "id": 1044,
                "question": "Which items are considered schema objects in Snowflake? (Choose two.)\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Pipe",
                  "B": "File format",
                  "C": "Resource monitor",
                  "D": "Storage integration",
                  "E": "Virtual warehouse"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A",
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "Schema objects in Snowflake are logical structures that reside within a database\nschema and define how data is organized and accessed. They are the building blocks for\ncreating and manipulating data within a Snowflake environment. Pipes and File Formats\nare indeed considered schema objects. Pipes automate the continuous loading of data\ninto Snowflake tables from external stages, while file formats specify the structure of\nthe data files being loaded or unloaded, such as CSV, JSON, or Avro. They are tied to the\nschema because they define how data is interpreted and loaded into the tables within\nthat specific schema.\nResource monitors, on the other hand, are account-level objects. They control credit\nusage for virtual warehouses at the account level, rather than being tied to a specific\nschema. Similarly, storage integrations are also account-level objects, defining how\nSnowflake interacts with external cloud storage services. Virtual warehouses, the\ncompute engines, are also not schema-level objects but are account or user-scoped\nresources. Therefore, options C, D, and E don't fit the definition of schema objects in\nSnowflake. Hence, only options A (Pipe) and B (File Format) are the correct choices.\nAuthoritative Links:Schema Objects: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/objects.html - This\nofficial Snowflake documentation provides a complete list of schema objects.\nPipes: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-load-snowpipe-intro.html Documentation on how pipes function and their integration with schemas.\nFile Formats: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/create-file-format.html Documentation specifying the syntax for creating file formats within a schema.\nAccount Objects: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/account-object-ddl.html\n- Documentation listing Account-level objects. This will also explain why they are not\nschema objects."
              },
              {
                "id": 1087,
                "question": "What objects in Snowflake are supported by Dynamic Data Masking? (Choose two.)\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Views",
                  "B": "Materialized views",
                  "C": "Tables",
                  "D": "External tables",
                  "E": "Future grants"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A",
                  "C"
                ],
                "explanation": "Dynamic Data Masking in Snowflake is a powerful feature that allows for the selective\nobfuscation of sensitive data based on user roles and policies, enhancing data security\nand compliance. The primary goal is to restrict access to sensitive data while still\nenabling users to work with it. Dynamic masking applies only to the data returned by\nqueries, and does not change underlying stored data.\nDynamic data masking is directly supported on two primary types of objects: Tables and\nViews. Tables are the foundation for storing raw data, and masking policies can be\ndirectly applied to columns within a table. Views, which are logical representations of\ndata from one or more tables, can also be masked. When a view is masked, the\nunderlying policy is applied as part of the view definition, effectively masking data\nreturned by queries against the view. Materialized views, which are pre-computed\nresults of a query, are not directly supported, as the data is already materialized and\ncannot be dynamically masked when accessed. External tables, pointing to data stored\noutside Snowflake, are also not supported due to their indirect data access pattern,\nwhere data access control is handled at the external storage level. Future grants, which\nare related to permissions and roles, are not data-bearing objects themselves, and thus\nare irrelevant for masking. Dynamic data masking focuses on data presentation and thus\napplies directly to tables and views.\nTherefore, the correct options are A. Views and C. Tables.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Dynamic Data Masking\nSnowflake Documentation on supported objects for masking policies"
              },
              {
                "id": 1175,
                "question": "Which Snowflake storage object can be used to store data beyond a single session and will not incur Fail-safe\ncosts?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Permanent table",
                  "B": "External table",
                  "C": "Temporary table",
                  "D": "Transient table"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D: Transient table. Let's break down why.\nPermanent tables are designed for long-term data storage and incur Fail-safe costs to\nprotect against data loss in the event of system failures. Fail-safe provides a 7-day (for\nEnterprise Edition and higher) period during which Snowflake retains the historical data\nnecessary for recovery by Snowflake. This is billed to the account.\nExternal tables store metadata about data residing in external storage locations (like\nAWS S3 or Azure Blob Storage). While the metadata itself is stored in Snowflake and is\nsubject to Fail-safe, the external data storage costs and data availability aspects are\nmanaged by the respective cloud provider, and they don't directly map to Snowflake's\nFail-safe. However, the Snowflake metadata about external tables does incur Fail-safe\ncosts.\nTemporary tables are designed for short-term data storage within a single session. They\nare automatically dropped at the end of the session in which they were created, so they\ndon't incur Fail-safe costs. However, they don't fulfill the requirement of storing data\nbeyond a single session.\nTransient tables, on the other hand, provide a middle ground. They persist data beyond a\nsingle session (like permanent tables), but they do not have Fail-safe. This makes them\nideal for data that requires persistence but is less critical and doesn't warrant the Failsafe protection and associated costs. Transient tables have a user-defined data\nretention period (up to 1 day), after which historical data is not recoverable through Time\nTravel or Fail-safe. If the data is corrupted or lost, you won't be able to rely on fail-safe to\nrecover it. Because there is no fail-safe, this satisfies the prompt requirements.\nTherefore, Transient tables are the only option that allows data to be stored beyond a\nsingle session without incurring Fail-safe costs.\nFor more information, refer to the Snowflake documentation:\nUnderstanding & Viewing Data Retention Period: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/data-availability.html#understanding-data-retention-period\nCREATE TABLE: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/create-table.html"
