quirement\neffectively.\nOption F is incorrect: Scaling up does not involve adding additional database servers. It refers to resizing an\nexisting virtual warehouse to a larger size.\nTherefore, options A and E accurately describe scaling out and scaling up in the context of Snowflake's\nvirtual warehouses.\nCloud Computing Concepts:\nVertical Scaling (Scale Up): Enhancing the capabilities of a single machine by increasing its CPU, memory,\nand other resources.\nHorizontal Scaling (Scale Out): Increasing capacity by adding more machines to the infrastructure.\nVirtual Warehouse: Snowflake's compute clusters that enable processing queries.\nConcurrency: The ability to handle multiple user requests at the same time.\nAuthoritative Links:\n1. Snowflake Documentation - Scaling Virtual Warehouses: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/warehouses-overview#scaling-virtual-warehouses\nThis page provides a detailed explanation of scaling options for virtual warehouses in Snowflake,\nexplicitly describing scale-up and scale-out scenarios.\n2. Snowflake Documentation - Multi-cluster Warehouses: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/warehouses-multicluster\nThis page explains how multi-cluster warehouses achieve scaling out which helps manage\nconcurency.\nThese resources from Snowflake's official documentation will deepen your understanding of the concepts\ndiscussed."
