olumn, changing a data type) doesn't always necessitate\na running warehouse immediately. Some metadata changes can be handled by the cloud services layer.\nHowever, if the alteration involves data transformations or significant restructuring, a warehouse will be\nrequired to process the data changes, potentially happening asynchronously.\nIn conclusion, Stored Procedures and Materialized Views require compute power to execute and serve results,\nrespectively. Altering a table (depending on the type of alteration), downloading files, and listing files might\nsometimes, but do not always, require a running warehouse. Therefore, C and E are the most appropriate\nanswers.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Virtual Warehouses: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/warehousesoverview.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Stored Procedures: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/storedprocedures.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Materialized Views: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/viewsmaterialized.html"
