                "choices": {
                  "A": "Increase the warehouse size.",
                  "B": "Use an economy scaling policy.",
                  "C": "Increase the maximum number of clusters.",
                  "D": "Convert the warehouse to a Snowpark-optimized warehouse."
                },
                "answer": [
                  "C"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is C. Increase the maximum number of clusters.\nHere's the justification:\nMulti-cluster virtual warehouses in Snowflake are designed to handle concurrent user\nrequests and workloads. When a warehouse experiences queuing, it means that\nincoming queries are waiting for resources to become available. Increasing the\nwarehouse size (A) can help in some cases by providing more compute resources per\ncluster, but it doesn't address the issue of resource contention when multiple queries\nare arriving simultaneously. An economy scaling policy (B) is primarily about cost\noptimization and may actually result in slower scaling, potentially exacerbating queuing.\nConverting to a Snowpark-optimized warehouse (D) addresses performance with\nSnowpark workloads, not necessarily general queuing issues.\nIncreasing the maximum number of clusters (C), on the other hand, allows Snowflake to\nautomatically create more compute resources when the existing clusters are at\ncapacity. This directly addresses the problem of queries waiting in a queue, by providing\nmore available clusters to handle the incoming requests. As demand increases,\nSnowflake adds more clusters, up to the defined maximum, and as demand decreases,\nSnowflake automatically suspends these extra clusters when they are no longer needed\nto save on costs. This dynamic scaling ensures efficient resource usage. By increasing\nthe max cluster count, you're telling Snowflake to be more proactive in allocating\nresources before queuing becomes an issue.\nTherefore, increasing the maximum number of clusters is the most effective approach to\nreduce queuing on a multi-cluster virtual warehouse.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Multi-cluster Warehouses:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/warehouses-multicluster.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Warehouse Scaling: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/warehouses-scaling.html"
              },
              {
                "id": 1086,
                "question": "What is the MOST cost-effective way to resolve memory spillage in a virtual warehouse?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Enable automatic clustering.",
                  "B": "Enable the query acceleration service.",
                  "C": "Enable the search optimization service.",
                  "D": "Convert to a Snowpark-optimized warehouse."
                },
                "answer": [
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. Convert to a Snowpark-optimized warehouse.\nMemory spillage occurs when a virtual warehouse doesn't have enough RAM to process\na query's data, forcing it to use slower disk storage. While options like auto-clustering\n(A) address data organization and query performance through micro-partitioning, they\ndon't directly alleviate RAM limitations during query execution. Query acceleration (B)\nand search optimization (C) focus on speeding up specific types of queries but don't\ndirectly address fundamental memory constraints.\nSnowpark-optimized warehouses, on the other hand, are specifically designed to\nexecute data processing logic using the Snowpark API within the Snowflake\nenvironment. This allows for pushdown of computations, meaning that data is processed\ncloser to the storage layer before being loaded into memory on the warehouse. By\nminimizing the amount of data loaded into RAM, they significantly reduce the likelihood\nof memory spillage. Snowpark's ability to leverage distributed processing on the\nSnowflake infrastructure further enhances resource efficiency by distributing the\nworkload. This architecture allows operations to be carried out more effectively across\nmany nodes. These optimizations make Snowpark-optimized warehouses the most costeffective approach for addressing memory spillage. They inherently improve efficiency\nand resource management related to data processing within a warehouse, rather than\nadjusting how the storage or searching works.\nFor further research on this topic, you can explore the following resources:\nSnowflake Documentation on Snowpark: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/developerguide/snowpark/index\nSnowflake Documentation on Virtual Warehouses: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/warehouses\nSnowflake Documentation on Query Profiling (for understanding spillage):https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile"
