                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. Increase the size of the virtual warehouse.\nHere's a detailed justification:\nThe problem statement highlights that the query is spending a significant amount of\ntime on remote disk I/O and consuming more credits than expected. Remote disk I/O\noccurs when the data needed for the query is not readily available in the virtual\nwarehouse's cache (local storage attached to the compute nodes). This forces the\nwarehouse to retrieve the data from Snowflake's remote storage layer (which is slowerand more expensive).\nIncreasing the size of the virtual warehouse provides more memory and local disk space\nto the compute nodes. This larger cache can hold more data, reducing the frequency of\nremote disk I/O operations. By keeping the frequently accessed data in the local cache,\nthe query can execute faster and more efficiently, leading to reduced credit\nconsumption. A larger warehouse has more CPU and memory allocated, further aiding\nwith query processing.\nOption A, \"Convert the virtual warehouse to Maximized mode,\" is incorrect. Maximized\nmode is generally used to minimize latency and maximize performance for workloads\nsensitive to even minor performance delays. While it can reduce latency, it doesn't\nspecifically address the remote disk I/O issue; it does not have direct cache sizing\nimplications and does not lower the frequency of I/O requests.\nOption C, \"Increase the auto suspend time in the virtual warehouse,\" is incorrect. Autosuspend controls how long a warehouse remains active when idle. It doesn't affect query\nperformance or remote disk I/O. Extending it only prevents the warehouse from shutting\ndown unnecessarily.\nOption D, \"Increase the number of clusters in the virtual warehouse,\" relates to multicluster warehouses which handles concurrency. Scaling out the number of clusters\nincreases concurrency handling but is not related to the initial query performance issues\nrelated to disk I/O as described.\nTherefore, increasing the virtual warehouse size is the most effective way to prevent the\nexcessive remote disk I/O and improve query performance, thus reducing credit\nconsumption.\nFurther Research:\nSnowflake Virtual Warehouse Sizing: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/warehouses-overview.html\nSnowflake Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-queryprofile.html"
