                "explanation": "The correct answer is C: The queries will be placed in a queue.\nHere's why: When a Snowflake virtual warehouse is fully utilized and lacks the resources\nto immediately execute incoming queries, Snowflake doesn't simply discard or redirect\nthem. Instead, it leverages a queuing mechanism. This mechanism ensures that queries\nare held in a waiting state until resources become available.\nOption A is incorrect because Snowflake doesn't automatically assign queries to a\ndifferent warehouse if the current warehouse is overloaded. Instead, multi-cluster\nwarehouses, if configured, may begin using the additional clusters within the same\nwarehouse definition. However, the question implies that the user is using a single\ncluster warehouse.\nOption B is also incorrect as Snowflake prioritizes executing queries rather than skipping\nthem. Skipping would lead to data loss and incomplete operations.\nOption D is partially correct; Snowflake can automatically resize if configured to autoscale. However, this takes time. During the resizing process, queries will still be queued.\nCrucially, the question doesn't state that auto-scaling is enabled. Also, a single-cluster\nwarehouse cannot resize. Since auto-scaling is not explicitly stated in the question, we\nneed to assume the warehouse will not resize and must queue the queries.\nThe queuing behavior allows Snowflake to maintain data integrity and avoid data loss.\nSnowflake's architecture is designed to handle bursts of activity and ensure all queries\neventually execute. Queuing is a standard practice in database management systems to\nmanage resource contention.Snowflake Documentation on Virtual\nWarehousesSnowflake Documentation on Query QueuingSnowflake Documentation on\nAuto-Scaling"
