                "id": 53,
                "question": "True or False: Snowflake charges additional fees to Data Providers for each Share they create.\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "True",
                  "B": "False"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The statement \"Snowflake charges additional fees to Data Providers for each Share they create\" is False.\nSnowflake's data sharing model is designed to be cost-effective and encourage data sharing. Data providers\nincur costs primarily based on the compute resources they use for data processing, storage, and services.\nHowever, creating a share itself is not an activity that triggers additional charges. The costs are borne by the\ndata consumer when they query the shared data, not the data provider for making the share available.Snowflake's cost model emphasizes consumption-based billing for compute and storage, ensuring providers\nare not penalized for broader data distribution. Shares are essentially pointers to data; they don't duplicate\nthe data or consume additional provider resources until that shared data is actively queried by a consumer.\nThink of it like providing a library card; the library doesn't charge for giving out cards but for borrowing the\nbooks. This is a key aspect of Snowflake’s value proposition, promoting efficient and cost-effective data\nsharing. The provider retains control of their data, and only pays for the underlying resources when the data is\nbeing processed or stored, whether by them or a consumer through sharing.\nFor further research, refer to the following resources:\nSnowflake Cost Optimization: https://www.snowflake.com/cost-optimization/\nSnowflake Secure Data Sharing: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-sharing-intro.html\nUnderstanding Snowflake's Billing: https://www.snowflake.com/pricing/"
              },
              {
                "id": 114,
                "question": "True or False: Data Providers can share data with only the Data Consumer.\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "True",
                  "B": "False"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The statement is False. Snowflake's Secure Data Sharing functionality allows Data Providers to share data\nwith multiple Data Consumers, not just one. This is a fundamental feature of the platform designed for widescale data collaboration. Data sharing in Snowflake is not a point-to-point relationship; instead, a Data\nProvider creates a \"share\" object and grants access to it for any number of authorized accounts. These\naccounts, acting as Data Consumers, can then access the data without requiring copies or data movement.\nThe share itself is a virtual construct, providing a live, read-only view of the provider's data. There are no limits\ninherent to the system that restricts a share to only one consumer account. This model facilitates broader\ndata distribution and eliminates the need for redundant ETL processes. Therefore, the statement asserting a\none-to-one sharing limitation is factually incorrect. Snowflake’s secure sharing mechanism promotes efficient\ndata monetization and cross-organizational data utilization.\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-sharing-introhttps://www.snowflake.com/blog/data-sharingsimplified/"
              },
