                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is CE. Let's break down why:\nOption C: A Snowflake account can both provide and consume shared data. This is correct. Snowflake allows\na single account to act as both a data provider (sharing data) and a data consumer (receiving data). This\nflexibility is a key aspect of Snowflake's data sharing architecture.\nOption E: The Data Consumer pays only for compute resources to query the shared data. This statement\naccurately reflects Snowflake's data sharing cost model. The data consumer pays for the compute resources\nused when querying the shared data. The data provider is not charged for compute resources used by the data\nconsumer when querying shared data.\nWhy the other options are incorrect:\nOption A: The Data Consumer pays for data storage as well as for data computing. The data consumer does\nnot pay for the data storage. The data provider pays for the storage of the data being shared.\nOption B: The shared data is copied into the Data Consumer account, so the Consumer can modify it without\nimpacting the base data of the Provider. Data sharing in Snowflake does not involve copying data. Instead, it\ngrants direct, secure access to the data in the provider's account. The consumer queries the data in place, so\nthey don't need to copy it into their account. It's a live, read-only view of the data, so the consumer can't\nmodify it.\nOption D: The Provider is charged for compute resources used by the Data Consumer to query the shared\ndata. This is incorrect. The data consumer pays for the compute costs when querying the shared data. The\nprovider does not incur these costs. This is a fundamental aspect of Snowflake's data sharing model.\nHere's why Snowflake's approach is beneficial:\nNo data duplication: Avoids the costs and complexities of copying data.\nReal-time access: Consumers always have access to the latest version of the data.\nSimplified management: Providers maintain control over their data and can easily revoke access.\nCost-effective: Consumers only pay for the compute resources they use.\nFor more information, refer to the official Snowflake documentation on secure data\nsharing:https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-sharing-intro.html\nAnd Snowflake's data sharing cost model:\nhttps://www.snowflake.com/blog/secure-data-sharing-in-snowflake/"
