                "explanation": "The correct answer is A because it accurately reflects the types of objects that can be shared in Snowflake.\nShares in Snowflake are the mechanism for securely sharing data and functionality with other Snowflake\naccounts. Crucially, shares themselves are not shared. Rather, they act as containers for database objects\nthat can be accessed by other accounts. These shareable objects include tables, secure views, and secure\nuser-defined functions (UDFs). This allows providers to selectively grant access to specific data assets and\ncustom logic, without needing to physically copy the data. Option B is incorrect because shares cannot be\nshared, they are the mechanism for sharing, not the thing being shared. Option C is incorrect because while\ndata consumers can query the data in shared tables they cannot directly clone from a share. Cloning occurs\nwithin a single account and not across accounts from shares. Option D is incorrect because access to a share\ncan absolutely be revoked, allowing providers to maintain control over who has access to their data. The\nSnowflake documentation clearly outlines that tables, secure views and secure UDFs are the primary\nshareable objects.\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-sharing-intro.htmlhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/create-share.html"
              },
