                "explanation": "Snowflake's secure sharing mechanism enables controlled access to data and functionalities across accounts\nwithout copying or moving the underlying data. Only specific object types are designed to participate in this\nsecure sharing model. Tables (D) are fundamental objects that hold data, and therefore are directly sharable.\nThe core concept of data sharing relies on granting access to tables so consumers can query the data within\nthe table but not alter it. Secure User-Defined Functions (UDFs) (E), specifically those defined as 'secure', can\nalso be shared. This allows the sharing of complex logic and computation within the data sharing relationship\nwithout exposing the underlying function implementation. However, Materialized Views (A) are not directly\nshared because they represent precomputed results based on a query. Sharing a Materialized view would not\nallow the consumer to modify or recompute the view. Sequences (B) are not shared. They are typically used to\ngenerate unique numeric values within an account and are tied to the specific instance. Similarly, Procedures\n(C) are not designed to be shared across accounts, as they often deal with imperative logic and data\nmanipulation within the local context. Therefore, Tables and Secure UDFs are the only sharable objects\namong the options.\nSnowflake Sharing Documentation\nSnowflake Secure UDF Documentation"
