                "explanation": "The correct answer is B and C: External tables and Secure User-Defined Functions (UDFs) can be shared via\nSnowflake's secure data sharing feature. Snowflake's secure data sharing mechanism facilitates sharing of\ndata without physically copying or moving it, granting read-only access to the shared objects. External tables,\nwhich point to data residing in external cloud storage locations like AWS S3, Azure Blob Storage, or Google\nCloud Storage, can be shared because Snowflake provides a way to grant access to the metadata defining the\nexternal data location and structure. Secure UDFs, which encapsulate custom logic, can also be shared. When\na secure UDF is shared, the recipient can execute the function without having visibility into its underlying\ncode, effectively sharing the functionality without revealing proprietary details. This promotes secure and\ncontrolled sharing of business logic. Files and Sequences, which are not typically objects containing data\ndirectly usable for analytical purposes, cannot be directly shared. Streams, being objects designed for\ntracking data manipulation within Snowflake databases, are specific to a single account and therefore are not\nshared via Snowflake's secure data sharing. Sharing is done via a Snowflake Share object, which acts as a\nnamed container of database objects for secure read-only access to shared data.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Data Sharing: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/share/data-sharing-intro.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Sharing External Tables: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/share/shareexternal-tables.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Sharing Secure UDFs: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql/udf-secureshare.html"
