                "explanation": "Justification for Answer A:\nWhen a data provider revokes privileges to a share on an object (like a table or view) within their source\ndatabase, the change is immediate and affects all data consumers who were previously granted access via\nthat share. This is because Snowflake's secure data sharing operates on a zero-copy architecture. Instead of\ncreating physical copies of data for each consumer, it relies on metadata and access controls. When the\nprovider revokes privileges, they are essentially removing the consumer's access to that metadata, rendering\nthe underlying data inaccessible. There is no lag time or grace period, and the data doesn't get copied\nelsewhere.\nOption B is incorrect because the data is completely inaccessible, not just updates. Option C is wrong as\nconsumers never become responsible for the source's storage charges since there are no copies created.\nOption D is incorrect as no static copy is made when the privileges are revoked. Since data is not physically\ncopied, revocation of share access immediately renders the data inaccessible. The consumer does not take on\nownership or have a snapshot of data after access removal.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Data Sharing: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-sharingintro.html This documentation provides an in-depth understanding of how Snowflake's secure data sharing\nworks and emphasizes the real-time nature of access control.\nSnowflake Documentation on Managing Shares: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/revokeshare.html This document specifically clarifies how revoking a share removes access for the data consumers\nand the immediate effect of that action."
