                "explanation": "The correct answer is AD. Here's a detailed justification:\nA. Provide each non-Snowflake supplier with their own reader account: Reader accounts are a Snowflake\nfeature that allows you to share data with consumers who are not already Snowflake customers. By providing\neach supplier with a dedicated reader account, you grant them secure and isolated access to the shared data.\nThis is a best practice because it avoids sharing credentials and maintains security. Each supplier gets its own\ndedicated compute resources for querying shared data, preventing performance issues associated with\nshared access.\nD. Use a data share for suppliers in the same cloud region and a replicated proxy share for other cloud\ndeployments: Snowflake's data sharing feature is the core mechanism for secure data sharing. For suppliers\nwithin the same cloud region as the provider, a direct data share is ideal. However, for suppliers in different\ncloud regions, a replicated proxy share becomes essential. A replicated proxy share creates a copy of the\ndata share in the supplier's region, minimizing latency and avoiding cross-region data transfer costs during\nquery execution. This ensures optimal performance and data locality for all suppliers, regardless of their\ngeographical location. Snowflake manages the replication process, simplifying the administrative overhead.\nWhy other options are incorrect:\nB. Deploy a single reader account to be shared by all of the non-Snowflake suppliers: This is a security risk.\nSharing a single reader account exposes the data to unauthorized access if the credentials are compromised.\nFurthermore, it's difficult to audit access and usage patterns of individual suppliers.\nC. Create an ETL pipeline that uses select and inserts statements from the source to the target supplier\naccounts: This involves building and maintaining a complex ETL pipeline, which is more costly and timeconsuming than using Snowflake's built-in data sharing capabilities. It also duplicates the data, increasing\nstorage costs and potentially introducing inconsistencies. Additionally, it bypasses Snowflake's built-in\nsecurity and governance features.\nE. Extract the shared transactional data to an external stage and use cloud storage utilities to reload the\nsuppliers' regions: While this approach could technically work, it's inefficient, complex, and insecure. It\nrequires constantly exporting and reloading the data, which can lead to data latency and inconsistencies. It\nalso introduces the risk of data breaches during the extraction and loading process. Snowflake data sharing is\na far more secure, efficient, and cost-effective solution.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Secure Data Sharing: https://www.snowflake.com/blog/secure-data-sharing-with-snowflake-howit-works-and-why-its-better/\nUsing Reader Accounts: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-sharing-reader-accounts.html\nData Replication: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/guides-replication.html"
