                "explanation": "Okay, let's analyze why option A is the correct answer and why the others are incorrect.\nData shares in Snowflake are fundamentally about providing secure, controlled access to data without\nphysically moving or copying it. Option A, stating \"Data shares support full DML operations,\" is incorrect. Data\nshares in Snowflake are designed for read-only access by consumers. They grant consumers the ability to\nquery (SELECT) the shared data but specifically do not allow them to modify it through DML operations like\nINSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE. This ensures data integrity and centralized control by the data provider.\nOption B, “Data shares work by copying data to consumer accounts,” is incorrect as data sharing in Snowflake\noperates on a metadata layer. It grants access to data residing in the provider’s account without creating\ncopies within the consumer's account. This is key to cost-efficiency and data governance. Snowflake’s\narchitecture allows seamless access without duplication.\nOption C, “Data shares utilize secure views for sharing view objects,” is incorrect. While secure views can be\nshared through shares, data shares can also share tables directly, without requiring a view as the\nintermediary. The ability to share views is just one capability of a share.\nOption D, “Data shares are cloud agnostic and can cross regions by default,” is incorrect. Snowflake data\nshares are not inherently cloud-agnostic and are tied to the specific Snowflake region the provider is using.\nData sharing across clouds or regions requires explicit configuration (through replication, for instance).\nTherefore, the core characteristic of a data share is that it facilitates secure, read-only access to data without\nphysical copies, meaning A is not correct. The most accurate understanding is that a data share grants access\nto data. Options B, C and D are all incorrect based on the mechanism of Snowflake’s sharing model.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Data Sharing: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-sharing-intro\nSnowflake Documentation on Secure Data Sharing: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-sharingsecure\nIt’s important to note that in the original response, the answer was incorrectly labeled as A. Based on the\nanalysis, A is incorrect and there is no right answer of the four options presented."
