                "explanation": "The correct action to enable sharing of a newly created Snowflake object with\nconsumers is to use the GRANT privilege ... TO SHARE command (option D). Snowflake\nemploys a role-based access control (RBAC) system, where specific privileges must be\nexplicitly granted to roles, which can then be assigned to users or other roles. Sharing\nobjects, such as tables, views, or functions, isn't automatic upon creation; it requires\nexplicit permission. Option A, \"automatic sharing,\" doesn't exist in Snowflake's design.\nObjects need explicit grants for access. Dropping and recreating the object (option B) or\nrenaming it (option C) are not methods of sharing; they're unnecessary and potentially\ndisruptive. The GRANT command is the standard way to assign privileges, including\nUSAGE, SELECT, INSERT, or others, on a specific object to a specific share. Snowflake\nshares act as secure containers for these grants, allowing you to share database objects\nwith external consumers securely. By using GRANT ... TO SHARE, you're explicitly\ndefining what users within a given share have permission to do with the object, ensuring\ndata governance and security. Shares are then used in combination with secure views or\nother masking techniques to manage access in even greater detail. Without granting\nnecessary privileges, consumers will not be able to see the shared object and its data, no\nmatter if they are internal to the account or external. Therefore, option D accurately\nreflects the Snowflake security model and best practices for data sharing.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on GRANT: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/grant-privilege\nSnowflake Documentation on Shares: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/datasharing-intro\nSnowflake Documentation on Access Control: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/security-access-control-overview"
