                "explanation": "The correct answer is C: alter share my_share add accounts = xy12345;. This command correctly adds the\nspecified account (xy12345) to the list of accounts that have access to the share my_share. In Snowflake, data\nsharing is managed through share objects. These objects act as containers defining what data is shared. To\ngrant access to a share, you must explicitly specify which accounts can consume the shared data. The ALTER\nSHARE command with the ADD ACCOUNTS clause is the designated method for this purpose.\nOption A, grant usage on share my_share to account xy12345;, is incorrect because it uses a GRANT statement,\nwhich is intended for granting privileges on database objects, not for directly adding consumer accounts to a\nshare. Option B, grant select on share my_share to account xy12345;, is also incorrect for similar reasons,\nfocusing on privileges rather than account association. Option D, alter account xy12345 add share my_share;, is\nincorrect because the share is modified, not the consumer account. Modifying the consumer account isn’t how\nSnowflake data sharing works. The account receiving the share has no mechanism to ‘add’ a share to itself; it\nhas to be explicitly granted access. The account receiving the share (the consumer) does not need to add or\nbe modified in order to receive a share.\nTherefore, only the ALTER SHARE command with the ADD ACCOUNTS clause achieves the required goal of\ngranting account xy12345 access to share my_share. This approach directly adds the account to the share's\naccess control list, enabling the user in account xy12345 to create a database from the share. The other\noptions either misuse GRANT or incorrectly attempt to modify the consumer account rather than the share\nobject.\nFor further research, please refer to the official Snowflake documentation on sharing data, specifically the\nALTER SHARE command:https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/altershare.htmlhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-sharing-intro.html"
