                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is AE. Let's break down why:\nOption A: \"Reader account users cannot add new data to the account.\" This is correct. Reader\naccounts are specifically designed for read-only access to data shared by a provider. They lack\nthe privileges to perform data modification operations, like inserting or updating records. This\nread-only limitation safeguards the provider's original data from unintended changes by the\nconsumer.\nOption E: \"Reader accounts enable data consumers to access and query data shared by the\nprovider.\" This is also correct. The core purpose of a reader account is to provide a secure channel\nfor a consumer to query and analyze data that a provider has shared with them. The shared data is\ndirectly accessible through the reader account, enabling analysis without requiring data\nduplication.\nLet's look at why the other options are incorrect:\nOption B: \"Reader account users can share data to other reader accounts.\" This is incorrect.\nReader accounts are consumers, not providers. They do not have the authorization to further share\nthe data they have access to with other accounts. Data sharing is exclusively controlled by the\nprovider who owns the data.\nOption C: \"A single reader account can consume data from multiple provider accounts.\" This is\nincorrect. While one provider account can share data with multiple reader accounts, a single\nreader account is usually linked to a single provider account for a specific sharing relationship.\nThe architecture enforces a clear and traceable relationship between a shared data source and a\nsingle consumer.\nOption D: \"Data consumers are responsible for reader account setup and data usage costs.\" This\nis incorrect. While the consumer interacts with and benefits from the reader account, the provider\nof the data is responsible for setting up and paying for the resources consumed by the reader\naccount. This model allows the data provider to retain control over costs associated with sharing\ntheir data.\nIn summary: Reader accounts offer a controlled, read-only access mechanism for data consumers.\nThey are designed to efficiently enable data sharing while preventing unauthorized data\nmodification and maintaining clear cost allocation on the provider side. The provider creates the\nreader account, shares the data, and is responsible for costs. The consumer queries the data.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Reader Accounts: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/datasharing-reader-accounts.html\nSnowflake Blog on Data Sharing: https://www.snowflake.com/blog/data-sharing-simplified-withsnowflake/ (This is a blog which gives an overview, not a direct documentation link)"
