                "explanation": "Snowflake, a cloud data platform, employs a unique approach to data storage and organization that is critical\nfor its performance and efficiency. When data is loaded into Snowflake, it undergoes a transformation\nprocess that significantly differs from traditional database systems. Firstly, Snowflake stores data in a\ncolumnar format. Unlike row-based storage where data for a single row is stored together, columnar storage\narranges data by column, meaning all values for a specific column are stored contiguously. This method is\nhighly beneficial for analytical workloads as queries often involve accessing only a subset of columns. By\nreading only the required column data, Snowflake avoids reading unnecessary data, leading to faster query\nexecution and reduced I/O operations.\nSecondly, Snowflake automatically compresses the stored data. This compression is essential for reducing\nstorage costs and improving data transfer speeds. Data compression techniques shrink the size of the data,\nwhich in turn minimizes the amount of storage required and the amount of data that needs to be moved across\nnetworks. Snowflake's compression is transparent to the user; that is, users do not need to specify the\ncompression type or handle decompression manually. The system automatically applies suitable algorithms\nfor optimal compression based on the data's characteristics.\nThe other options are not correct. Binary format (A) is a fundamental storage format and not a reorganization\nstrategy. Raw format (D) refers to unprocessed data. Zipped format (E) is a specific compression method,\nwhile Snowflake uses various automatic compression techniques and is not limited to zipping. Thus, the\ncorrect transformations are columnar formatting and compression.\nFor further reading, consider the following resources:\nSnowflake Documentation on Micro-partitions (which inherently involves columnar storage):\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/data-micro-partitions\nSnowflake Documentation on Data Compression: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/datacompressionThese resources will provide further insight into Snowflake's data architecture and its benefits."
