                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. Pruning. Snowflake utilizes a technique called partition pruning (or micropartition pruning) to optimize query performance by minimizing the amount of data scanned.\nSnowflake automatically organizes data into immutable micro-partitions, each containing\ncolumnar data. When a query is executed, Snowflake's query optimizer analyzes the query's\npredicates (WHERE clause conditions). Using metadata about the values within each micropartition, the optimizer determines which partitions do not contain any data that could satisfy the\nquery. These partitions are then “pruned,” meaning they are not scanned at all during query\nexecution. This selective scanning drastically reduces I/O operations and improves query speed.\nThis contrasts with other approaches; B-trees are indexing structures used for efficient lookups\nbut not directly for partition selection in this manner. Indexing, as a concept, exists in Snowflake\nbut primarily as search optimization and does not remove partitions themselves. Map Reduce is a\nparallel processing model used for big data but doesn't relate to partition elimination in\nSnowflake. Pruning is specific to optimizing the scanning of partitioned data. By examining\npartition metadata for min/max values and other statistics, Snowflake eliminates unnecessary\ndisk reads and achieves significant performance improvements. The process is transparent to the\nuser and requires no manual configuration.\nSnowflake Documentation on Micro-partitionsSnowflake Documentation on Query Optimization"
