                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. The use of pruning.\nSnowflake significantly enhances the performance of queries filtering large amounts of data\nprimarily through a technique called pruning. Pruning is a query optimization strategy where\nSnowflake intelligently avoids scanning unnecessary data files by leveraging metadata about the\ndata distribution within those files. Instead of reading every file, Snowflake only reads the specific\ndata files that contain data relevant to the query's filter conditions. This is highly efficient\nbecause it dramatically reduces the amount of I/O operations needed to process the query.\nOptions A, C, and D are not primarily how Snowflake optimizes filtered queries:\nIndexing (A): While Snowflake utilizes a form of micro-partitioning, it does not rely on traditional\ndatabase indexes. The data within each micro-partition is already organized in a columnar fashion\nwhich allows very fast retrieval. It is also the mechanism that enables effective pruning.\nTableScan (C): A table scan means examining all data in a table, which is the opposite of what\nSnowflake aims to achieve for filtered queries. Therefore, it would be less efficient.\nIncreasing the number of partitions scanned (D): This would increase the data to be scanned and\nthus reduce efficiency, also this statement goes opposite to Snowflake’s objective which is to\nreduce the scanned data.\nPruning is a key concept in columnar databases like Snowflake. These databases store data\ncolumn-wise, which enables them to easily access specific columns needed for a query. When\ncombined with pruning, column-wise storage becomes extremely efficient.Essentially, Snowflake’s efficient processing hinges on its ability to use metadata about the\nmicro-partitions to avoid reading the ones that contain data that won't satisfy the filtering\nconditions. This focused approach minimizes unnecessary processing, leading to significantly\nfaster query execution.\nFurther Reading:\nSnowflake Documentation on Micro-partitions and Pruning: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/tables-clustering-keys.html#pruning-data-files\nSnowflake Documentation on Micro-partitions: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/datapartitioning.html#micro-partitions"
