                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "Here's a detailed justification for why option B is the correct answer, along withsupporting explanations:\nClustering depth in Snowflake is a measure of how well the data within a table is\norganized based on its clustering key. A clustering depth of 1 signifies that, on average,\neach micro-partition in the table overlaps with only one other micro-partition, or, more\ntechnically, the average overlap is only 1. This doesn't mean the table has only one\nmicro-partition (ruling out A), nor does it mean there are no micro-partitions (ruling out\nD). Instead, it describes the degree of overlap between micro-partitions. With a\nclustering depth of 1, there is overlap, but it is limited; the data is not perfectly colocated according to the clustering key. The goal of good clustering is to minimize\noverlap. A clustering depth of 1 represents a somewhat poor clustering state as it's still\nlikely that queries will need to scan more micro-partitions than necessary, leading to\nless efficient query performance. A clustering depth of 0, which is what option C is\ndescribing, would represent perfect clustering with no overlap between micro-partitions.\nOption B, stating that the table has 1 overlapping micro-partition, is the most accurate\ninterpretation of a clustering depth of 1. It doesn't imply a literal single overlap but\nrather that the average overlap is one, which is how clustering depth is calculated. Lower\nclustering depths, ideally closer to zero, are desired to optimize query performance by\nreducing the number of micro-partitions that Snowflake needs to scan. High clustering\ndepths, conversely, indicate poor organization which can translate into costly queries.\nAuthoritative links for further research:\nSnowflake Documentation on Clustering: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/tables-clustering.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Clustering Depth: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/functions/clustering_information.html\nThese resources will provide deeper context on micro-partitioning and the impact of\nclustering on performance."
