                "explanation": "The correct answer is B because Snowflake's query optimization relies heavily on its\nmicro-partition architecture and metadata. Here's a detailed explanation:\nSnowflake stores data in micro-partitions, which are small, contiguous units of storage\n(typically 50-500MB uncompressed). Each micro-partition stores metadata about the\ndata it contains, including the range of values for each column.When a query is executed, Snowflake leverages this metadata to perform what's called\n\"micro-partition pruning.\" This means Snowflake first checks the metadata of each\nmicro-partition to determine if it contains any data that could satisfy the query's filtering\ncriteria (WHERE clause). Micro-partitions that don't contain relevant data are entirely\nskipped (pruned) from the query execution plan. This significantly reduces the amount of\ndata that needs to be scanned, resulting in faster query performance.\nAfter the irrelevant micro-partitions are pruned, Snowflake proceeds to filter the rows\nwithin the remaining micro-partitions based on the query's selection criteria. Because\nonly relevant micro-partitions are scanned at this stage, the filtering operation is much\nmore efficient. Snowflake does not initially prune data by column to eliminate micropartitions. The pruning decisions are made based on column values stored in the\nmetadata associated with each micro-partition. The data within each micro-partition are\nin columnar format.\nOption A is incorrect because Snowflake first prunes by micro-partition (using metadata)\nbefore filtering rows. It doesn't \"prune by column to eliminate micro-partitions.\"\nOption C is incorrect because the data is not pruned by column within the remaining\nmicro-partitions; rows are filtered instead. Column-level pruning at the micro-partition\nlevel doesn't align with Snowflake's architecture.\nOption D is incorrect because while data is physically organized in columnar fashion\nwithin micro-partitions, the initial optimization step involves micro-partition pruning\nbefore filtering rows. Row sorting within the micro-partitions is also not the primary\nfocus of this specific optimization technique described in the question.\nTherefore, answer B accurately describes Snowflake's optimization process: it first\nprunes irrelevant micro-partitions based on column values stored in metadata, then it\nfilters the rows within the remaining micro-partitions to return the final result set.\nFurther Research:\nSnowflake Documentation on Micro-Partitions: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/tables-clustering-micropartitions.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Data Organization: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/data-load-transform.html"
