                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D: Once established, they cannot be changed.\nSnowflake micro-partitions are immutable once created. This fundamental\ncharacteristic contributes significantly to Snowflake's data consistency, performance,\nand concurrency control. Immutability means that after a micro-partition is written to\nstorage, its contents are never directly modified. Instead, updates or deletes result in\nnew micro-partitions being created.\nThis immutability is crucial for several reasons. Firstly, it enables efficient and reliable\ntime travel. Because old versions of data are preserved in their original micro-partitions,\nusers can query historical data without impacting current workloads. Secondly, it\nsimplifies concurrency control. Since micro-partitions are never modified in place,\nmultiple queries can safely access the same data without needing complex locking\nmechanisms. Thirdly, immutability supports Snowflake's caching strategy. Once a\nmicro-partition is cached, it remains valid unless explicitly evicted, improving query\nperformance by minimizing disk I/O. Fourthly, it facilitates secure data sharing. Sharing\ndata between accounts is simpler and safer because there's no risk of one account\ncorrupting data owned by another through in-place modifications. When data changes\nare made, new micro-partitions will be generated containing the updated data and the\nprevious micro-partition will still exist in its original form. The metadata layer tracks\nwhich micro-partitions are \"active\" for a given point in time.\nOption A is incorrect because micro-partitions are not directly exposed as files.\nSnowflake manages their storage internally. Option B is incorrect because while micropartitions contain metadata used for optimization, they are not themselves the index.\nSnowflake employs a metadata layer that provides sophisticated indexing capabilities\nbased on micro-partition characteristics. Option C is incorrect because micro-partition\nsize is primarily influenced by data volume and internal optimization strategies, and is\nnot directly tied to time travel configuration.For further details, consult Snowflake's\nofficial documentation on micro-partitions: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/tables-internal-structures.html"
