                  "B": "Increasing the virtual warehouse maximum timeout limit",
                  "C": "Increasing the amount of remote storage for the virtual warehouse",
                  "D": "Using a Common Table Expression (CTE) instead of a temporary table"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is A: Using a larger virtual warehouse. Data spilling in Snowflake occurs when\na virtual warehouse lacks sufficient memory to process a query's intermediate results. These\nresults are then written to local storage or, if that's exhausted, to remote storage. This process,\nknown as \"spilling,\" significantly degrades query performance due to slower I/O operations\ncompared to in-memory processing. A larger virtual warehouse has more compute resources,\nincluding RAM, allowing it to hold more data in memory. This reduces the likelihood of spilling and\nkeeps the query processing within the fast memory layer, improving overall query speed.\nIncreasing the warehouse's maximum timeout (B) will not affect data spill, as it only determines\nhow long the query can run. Increasing remote storage (C) won't prevent spills; it simply provides\na slower location to store spilled data once memory is exhausted. Finally, using CTEs (D), while\nimproving query readability and modularity, has no direct impact on resource allocation or spilling\nbehavior.\nLarger virtual warehouse sizes directly increase the available memory for query execution,\nthereby reducing spilling. This aligns with the principle of resource allocation to match workload\ndemands in cloud computing. The goal is to optimize performance by aligning the provisioned\nresources with processing needs. When resources are adequate, the query runs efficiently.\nReferences:\nSnowflake Documentation: Understanding and Optimizing Performance\nSnowflake Documentation: Virtual Warehouses"
