                "explanation": "The correct answer is A (Auto-suspend) and D (Resource monitor). Let's break down why.\nVirtual warehouses in Snowflake are compute engines, and their efficient management\nis crucial for cost optimization. Auto-suspend directly contributes to this. It's a property\nthat defines the inactivity period after which the warehouse automatically suspends,\npreventing unnecessary consumption of compute credits when not in use. This is a\nstandard cloud computing practice for cost savings.\nResource monitors allow administrators to control the credit consumption of awarehouse (or a group of warehouses). By attaching a resource monitor to a warehouse,\nadministrators can set limits and receive alerts when usage approaches these limits.\nThis is also a core aspect of cloud cost governance and resource management.\nOption B, Cache size, is incorrect. The cache size is automatically managed by Snowflake\nand cannot be manually configured by the user. Snowflake's data caching mechanism is\ndesigned to optimize query performance without requiring user intervention.\nOption C, Default role, while important for user management, is not a property set when\ncreating the warehouse itself. The default role is associated with the user account,\ndictating the privileges they possess upon connecting to Snowflake.\nOption E, Storage size, is also incorrect. Virtual warehouses do not manage storage\ndirectly. Snowflake's storage layer is independent of the compute layer (virtual\nwarehouses). The storage is managed by Snowflake itself, and users don't configure\nwarehouse properties related to data storage.\nIn summary, Auto-suspend and Resource monitor are properties directly configurable\nduring virtual warehouse creation to manage cost and resource utilization, aligning with\ncore principles of cloud resource management and Snowflake's design.\nFor further research, you can refer to the following Snowflake documentation:\nVirtual Warehouse Properties\nResource Monitors"
