                "explanation": "The correct answer is C. Enable auto-suspend to a low value to minimize credit\nconsumption during inactivity.\nSnowflake virtual warehouses consume credits based on the time they are actively\nrunning. When a warehouse is idle, meaning it's not processing queries, it still incurs\ncosts if it remains active. The auto-suspend feature is designed to automatically shut\ndown the warehouse after a specified period of inactivity. Setting this period to a low\nvalue, such as a few minutes, ensures that the warehouse quickly suspends when not in\nuse. This directly translates to reduced credit consumption, optimizing cost efficiency.\nConversely, setting a high value or disabling auto-suspend would keep the warehouse\nrunning unnecessarily, leading to wasted credits and higher expenses.\nOption A is incorrect because maximizing auto-suspend duration would mean keeping\nthe warehouse active for extended idle periods, which contradicts the principle of cost\noptimization. Option B is also incorrect; while maximizing availability seems good, it\ncomes at a cost; a perpetually active warehouse wastes resources. Option D is incorrect\nfor the same reason as option B. Continuous availability without auto-suspend is rarely\njustified outside specific, highly demanding use cases.\nSnowflake's recommendation is to find a balance between availability and cost, and a\nlow auto-suspend value, in conjunction with auto-resume, helps achieve this by ensuring\nwarehouses are quickly suspended when inactive but automatically spin up when\nneeded. This approach embodies cloud computing's core principle of elasticity and payper-use. The goal is to utilize resources only when needed and avoid charges during idle\nperiods, which is directly achieved by a low auto-suspend value.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Virtual Warehouse Auto-Suspend:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/warehouses-auto-suspend-auto-resume\nSnowflake Cost Optimization Best Practices: https://www.snowflake.com/blog/costoptimization-best-practices/"
