              {
                "id": 39,
                "question": "True or False: Query ID's are unique across all Snowflake deployments and can be used in communication with\nSnowflake Support to help troubleshoot issues.\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "True",
                  "B": "False"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A"
                ],
                "explanation": "The statement is True. Snowflake generates unique Query IDs for every query executed within its system.\nThese IDs are not just unique within a single Snowflake account or region, but they are globally unique across\nall Snowflake deployments. This global uniqueness is a fundamental design aspect of the platform. This\nfeature allows Snowflake Support to quickly and accurately identify the exact query that a user is referring to\nwhen troubleshooting issues. When you contact Snowflake Support, providing the Query ID allows them to\ndirectly access the execution details, including the SQL statement, execution time, resources used, and any\nerrors encountered. This enables significantly faster and more effective problem resolution. Without globally\nunique IDs, support would face substantial challenges in pinpointing specific queries across the vast,\ndistributed Snowflake environment. This is a key aspect of the scalability and reliability that Snowflake offers.\nRelying on descriptive information such as time of execution or user name can be ambiguous and would not\naccurately identify the single query in question. The ability to track and analyze specific queries via globallyunique Query IDs is crucial to Snowflake's architecture, particularly with its cloud-native distributed\napproach.\nRelevant Documentation:\nSnowflake documentation on Query IDs: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-queryhistory.html#query-ids"
              },
              {
                "id": 60,
                "question": "The Query History in the Snowflake Web Interface (UI) is kept for approximately:\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "60 minutes",
                  "B": "24 hours",
                  "C": "14 days",
                  "D": "30 days",
                  "E": "1 year"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "C"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is C, 14 days. Snowflake retains query history in the Web UI for a period of 14 days by\ndefault. This history includes details about executed queries, such as the query text, user who executed it,\nstart and end times, and other execution metrics. This time limit is a built-in feature of the platform's auditing\nand monitoring capabilities, designed to provide a recent view of query activity for debugging and analysis.\nWhile Snowflake offers query history through other methods like the QUERY_HISTORY view, the Web UI\nretains it for a shorter period. The 14-day limit serves as a compromise between providing useful recent data\nand managing storage costs and performance. Information older than 14 days will still be available through\nother mechanisms, but is not displayed directly in the web UI's Query History. Users needing longer retention\nshould utilize those other mechanisms for tracking historical query data. Options A, B, D, and E are incorrect\nas they do not reflect the default retention period of the Web UI query history in Snowflake. The specific 14day limit helps facilitate efficient troubleshooting and performance analysis. This period also avoids\noverloading the UI with a massive backlog of historical information.\nFor further research, refer to the official Snowflake documentation on query history:\nSnowflake Query History\nSnowsight query history"
              },
              {
                "id": 143,
                "question": "When reviewing a query profile, what is a symptom that a query is too large to fit into the memory?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "A single join node uses more than 50% of the query time",
                  "B": "Partitions scanned is equal to partitions total",
                  "C": "An AggregateOperator node is present",
                  "D": "The query is spilling to remote storage"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. The query is spilling to remote storage. Here's a detailed justification:\nWhen a Snowflake query's memory requirements exceed the available resources, the system resorts to\n\"spilling\" data to remote storage (typically cloud storage like S3 or Azure Blob Storage). This is a clear\nindication that the query is too large to fit entirely within memory. This process involves writing intermediate\ndata sets to storage and reading them back during query execution.\nOption A is incorrect; a join node using a significant portion of query time might indicate inefficient join\nstrategies or large data sizes but not necessarily memory overflow. Option B is also incorrect; partitions\nscanned being equal to partitions total means the query scanned all relevant data and is not related to\nmemory problems. Option C is incorrect; the presence of an AggregateOperator is normal and does not\nsuggest the query is too large for memory.\nSpilling introduces significant latency as it involves I/O operations that are much slower than in-memory\nprocessing. This can drastically increase the execution time of the query. The query profile in Snowflake will\nexplicitly show when spilling occurs, often highlighting it as a performance bottleneck. Efficient query design\naims to minimize or avoid spilling by using filters, efficient join methods, and potentially partitioning or\nclustering tables.\nKey takeaway is that spilling is a direct consequence of memory limitations, whereas other options can be\nrelated to different performance factors.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile Specifically, look for sections discussing memory usage and spilling.\nSnowflake Performance Tuning: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/performance-tuning - This\nsection provides an overview of potential performance bottlenecks and how to optimize queries."
              },
              {
                "id": 187,
                "question": "What is an advantage of using an explain plan instead of the query profiler to evaluate the performance of a\nquery?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "The explain plan output is available graphically.",
                  "B": "An explain plan can be used to conduct performance analysis without executing a query.",
                  "C": "An explain plan will handle queries with temporary tables and the query profiler will not.",
                  "D": "An explain plan's output will display automatic data skew optimization information."
                },
                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is B: An explain plan can be used to conduct performance analysis without executing a\nquery. Here's a detailed justification:\nExplain plans provide a breakdown of how Snowflake intends to execute a query, outlining the steps involved\nin retrieving and processing data. Critically, this plan is generated without actually running the query. This is\ninvaluable for identifying potential performance bottlenecks before incurring the cost and time associated\nwith execution. You can see if a full table scan is happening when an index would be more appropriate.\nThe query profiler, in contrast, requires the query to be executed. It analyzes the query execution after it has\ncompleted, providing detailed runtime statistics about each operation. While the profiler is extremely useful\nfor pinpointing performance issues in already executed queries, it's not suitable for preemptive analysis.\nRunning an explain plan also has no costs associated with it.\nOption A is incorrect because while Snowflake's web interface provides a graphical representation of the\nquery profile, it doesn't offer a graphical output for the explain plan itself. The explain plan output is typically\ntextual or in JSON format.\nOption C is incorrect. Both explain plans and the query profiler can handle queries involving temporary tables.\nTemporary tables simply exist for the duration of the session or query in which they are created.\nOption D is also incorrect. While Snowflake automatically performs data skew optimizations, the explain\nplan's primary focus isn't to display detailed data skew optimization information. The profiler contains this\ninformation. It outlines the intended execution path, not necessarily the specific optimizations applied to\naddress skew.\nIn summary, the key advantage of an explain plan is its ability to predict query performance issues before\nexecution, offering a cost-effective and time-saving method for query optimization.Snowflake Documentation\non EXPLAINSnowflake Documentation on Query Profile"
              },
              {
                "id": 224,
                "question": "In the query profiler view for a query, which components represent areas that can be used to help optimize query\nperformance? (Choose two.)\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Bytes scanned",
                  "B": "Bytes sent over the network",
                  "C": "Number of partitions scanned",
                  "D": "Percentage scanned from cache",
                  "E": "External bytes scanned"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "A",
                  "C"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct options that directly relate to optimizing query performance in Snowflake's Query Profiler are\nNumber of partitions scanned (C) and Percentage scanned from cache (D).\nHere's the justification:\nNumber of partitions scanned (C): Snowflake organizes data into micro-partitions. When a query executes,\nSnowflake aims to scan only the relevant partitions. If a query scans a high number of partitions relative to the\ntotal number available, it suggests inefficient filtering or missing clustering keys. Reducing the number of\npartitions scanned is a key optimization goal. This can be achieved by adding appropriate WHERE clauses,\nleveraging clustering, or using materialized views. Scanning fewer partitions directly reduces the amount of\ndata that Snowflake needs to process, leading to faster query execution.\nPercentage scanned from cache (D): Snowflake's caching mechanism stores frequently accessed data in\nmemory (both warehouse and result cache). A high percentage of data being scanned from the cache\nindicates efficient data reuse and significantly faster query times because retrieving data from cache is much\nfaster than retrieving it from storage. Conversely, a low cache hit rate implies that data is not being efficiently\nreused, potentially because the data is not accessed frequently or the cache is getting invalidated or the\nwarehouse is too small. Increasing the percentage scanned from cache improves efficiency.\nOptions A (Bytes scanned) and B (Bytes sent over the network) are important metrics, but they are results of\nthe underlying processing, not levers you directly manipulate for optimization. While reducing bytes scanned\nindirectly improves performance, it is achieved by reducing partitions scanned. Reducing bytes sent over the\nnetwork is important for client response time but is not a primary concern of the query profiler. Bytes scanned\nis a general metric reflecting the overall data processed, which is a symptom of inefficiency if partitions\nscanned is too high. External bytes scanned (E) would be relevant if your query involved external tables.\nTherefore, the focus should be on reducing the number of partitions scanned and increasing the percentage\nscanned from the cache.\nSupporting Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Query Profiling: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-queryprofile.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Data Clustering: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tables-clustering-keys.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Caching: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/querying-using-cache.html"
              },
              {
                "id": 249,
                "question": "A sales table FCT_SALES has 100 million records.\nThe following query was executed:\nSELECT COUNT (1) FROM FCT_SALES;\nHow did Snowflake fulfill this query?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Query against the result set cache",
                  "B": "Query against a virtual warehouse cache",
                  "C": "Query against the most-recently created micro-partition",
                  "D": "Query against the metadata cache"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. Query against the metadata cache.\nHere's a detailed justification:\nSnowflake's architecture leverages metadata extensively for query optimization. When a COUNT(1) query is\nexecuted against a table without any filtering conditions (like WHERE clauses), Snowflake doesn't need to\nscan the actual data stored in micro-partitions. Instead, it can retrieve the total row count from the metadata\ncache. This cache maintains summary information about the table, including the number of rows.\nThis approach offers significant performance benefits. Directly accessing the metadata is much faster than\nscanning and aggregating values from the numerous micro-partitions containing the actual table data. This\nefficiency is fundamental to Snowflake's speed and cost optimization. A metadata cache lookup is a quick\noperation, avoiding the need to engage a virtual warehouse for extensive data processing, ultimately leading\nto significant cost savings.\nThe result set cache (option A) is relevant for queries that retrieve and compute data. Since the count query\nonly needs aggregated metadata and is not retrieving actual data, the result set cache is not used here.\nVirtual warehouse cache (option B) is related to the processed data cached after executing more complex\nqueries. The metadata cache (option D), on the other hand, maintains precomputed aggregates like total row\ncounts and is designed for this precise scenario. Option C is incorrect because micro-partitions contain the\nactual data, and a COUNT(1) query against a whole table wouldn't involve accessing the data within even the\nmost recent micro-partition directly if it can extract the results from metadata..\nIn summary, Snowflake optimizes this type of COUNT(1) query by directly fetching the total row count from\nits metadata cache, bypassing the need to process data from micro-partitions.\nAuthoritative Links for Further Research:\nSnowflake Documentation on Metadata Caching: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/queryingmetadata\nSnowflake Architecture Overview: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/introduction\nMicro-partitions in Snowflake: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tables-micro-partitions"
              },
              {
                "id": 265,
                "question": "Which Query Profile result indicates that a warehouse is sized too small?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "There are a lot of filter nodes.",
                  "B": "Bytes are spilling to external storage.",
                  "C": "The number of processed rows is very high.",
                  "D": "The number of partitions scanned is the same as partitions total."
                },
                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. Bytes are spilling to external storage.\nHere's a detailed justification:\nSnowflake's Query Profile provides insights into query execution and performance. When a warehouse is\nundersized for the workload, it lacks sufficient memory to process the data in-memory. Consequently,\nintermediate results and data that would typically reside in memory during query execution are forced to spill\nto external storage (typically cloud storage like AWS S3 or Azure Blob Storage). This spilling significantly\ndegrades query performance because accessing data on external storage is much slower than accessing data\nin memory. Reading and writing to external storage introduce I/O bottlenecks and latency.\nOption A (a lot of filter nodes) indicates complex filtering logic but not necessarily undersized warehouse. It\nmay rather point to poorly optimized query. Option C (number of processed rows is very high) may be\nacceptable and unavoidable if dealing with huge data volumes, but spilling represents the warehouse’s\nlimitations in handling these rows. Option D (number of partitions scanned is the same as partitions total)\nsuggest possible full table scans, related to missing or ineffective filtering, and less about memory capacity\nof the warehouse.\nThe key concept is the limited memory resources of an undersized warehouse. It cannot hold the data needed,\nso the system has to use slower, external storage. Spotting spilling in query profile is a clear sign for\nwarehouse scaling. Therefore, spilled bytes in the query profile is a direct indicator of a warehouse that is not\nadequately sized to handle the query's memory requirements, ultimately impacting performance. A larger\nwarehouse provides more memory and reduces the likelihood of spilling to external storage.\nFurther resources for research:\nSnowflake Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile.html\nSnowflake Warehouse Sizing: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/warehouses-considerations.html"
