                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. Remote spillage. Here's why:\nRemote spillage in Snowflake's query profile directly indicates that the virtual warehouse lacks sufficient\nresources (specifically, memory) to process the data in memory. When a warehouse runs out of memory, it\nstarts \"spilling\" data to disk, which is significantly slower. This spilling can be local (to the warehouse nodes)\nor remote (to cloud storage), with remote spillage being the more severe performance bottleneck. The query\nprofiler variable related to spillage is called \"spilled to local\" or \"spilled to remote\" . Initialization,\nsynchronization, and network bytes sent are all related to different aspects of query execution but don't\nexplicitly point to inadequate warehouse size. While network traffic can be heavy in some cases, it does not\nshow the lack of warehouse resources like spillage does. Initialization time would be more related to the initial\nstart up of the warehouse. Synchronization time would involve coordinating different operations within the\nwarehouse, but it does not directly indicate an under-sized warehouse. Remote spillage, however, explicitly\nshows that the allocated memory wasn't sufficient for the work, forcing the system to resort to much slower\ndisk-based operations. This clearly points to a warehouse that needs to be scaled up to better accommodate\nthe query's needs. When spillage is high, it's recommended to scale up the virtual warehouse. Remote spillage\nin Snowflake will significantly impact the query's performance, making it the most obvious indicator of an\nundersized virtual warehouse.\nFor further research, you can consult the following Snowflake documentation:\nUnderstanding the Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile.html\n(Specifically look for \"Spilled to Local/Remote\" or \"Spilling\")\nVirtual Warehouse Sizing: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/warehouses-overview.html#warehousesizing"
