                "answer": [
                  "C",
                  "E"
                ],
                "explanation": "Here's the justification for why options C (Partitions total) and E (Partitions scanned) are the correct choices\nfor identifying efficient pruning in Snowflake query profiles:\nEfficient pruning is a fundamental optimization technique in columnar databases like Snowflake. It minimizes\nthe amount of data read from storage by skipping irrelevant data partitions based on query predicates. To\ndetermine if pruning is working effectively, you need to understand how many data partitions exist and how\nmany were actually processed.\nPartitions Total (C): This statistic reveals the total number of micro-partitions that exist for the tables\ninvolved in the query. This is a critical reference point. It tells you the potential amount of data that could be\nscanned.\nPartitions Scanned (E): This statistic indicates the actual number of micro-partitions that Snowflake had to\nread to satisfy the query.\nBy comparing the \"Partitions Total\" with \"Partitions Scanned,\" you can determine the pruning effectiveness. A\nsignificant difference between these numbers indicates that a large number of micro-partitions were pruned\nbased on the filtering conditions of the query. If \"Partitions Scanned\" is close to \"Partitions Total,\" it suggestsminimal pruning, indicating a potential performance bottleneck due to unnecessary data scanning. This could\nsignal the need for adjustments to the query or data clustering for better pruning.\nOptions A (Bytes sent over network) and D (Bytes spilled to local storage) are related to data transfer and\nresource management, but do not directly show how effective the pruning process was before any data\ntransfer or storage. Option B (Percentage scanned from cache) is relevant to performance; however, it\nfocuses on how much data was retrieved from cache, not the pruning of data from storage.\nIn summary, the combination of \"Partitions total\" and \"Partitions scanned\" gives the clearest picture of how\nwell Snowflake is pruning data during a query execution. A large disparity suggests effective pruning, which\nleads to efficient query execution and cost savings.\nAuthoritative Links for Further Research:\nSnowflake Documentation on Micro-partitions: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tables-clusteringmicropartitions\nSnowflake Documentation on Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile\nSnowflake Documentation on Understanding Pruning\nhttps://community.snowflake.com/s/article/Understanding-Pruning-in-Snowflake"
