                "explanation": "The correct answers are D and E. Snowflake's Query Profile is a powerful tool for analyzing query\nperformance after execution, not before (eliminating A). It provides a detailed breakdown of query execution,\nhighlighting areas where performance bottlenecks occur. Option B is incorrect because while you can\nindirectly infer credit usage from query duration and resource consumption displayed in the profile, it doesn't\ndirectly state credit consumption. Option C is also incorrect as the Query Profile doesn't identify logical errors\nin the SQL, but instead helps identify performance issues.\nOption D, \"Identifying inefficient micro-partition pruning,\" is a key use case for the Query Profile. Micropartition pruning is a crucial optimization technique where Snowflake filters out unnecessary data by\nleveraging metadata stored for micro-partitions. The profile will highlight scenarios where this pruning isn't\neffective, indicating inefficiencies and potential performance improvements by re-evaluating the query\nstructure or table clustering. The query profile shows the \"Partitions scanned\" in relation to the \"Total\nPartitions\", allowing you to determine how well partitioning is working.\nOption E, \"Data spilling to a local or remote disk,\" is another common issue the profile reveals. When query\nprocessing exceeds available memory, Snowflake may start spilling data to disk, slowing down execution\ndramatically. The profile clearly indicates these spills, providing valuable insight for optimization, such as\nresizing the warehouse, modifying query to reduce intermediate data size, or adjusting data types. The\noperator steps under the \"Execution/Operators\" tab will display spilling related information.\nTherefore, identifying inefficient micro-partition pruning and data spilling are the most frequent and directly\nobservable issues via the Query Profile.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Micro-partitioning: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tablesclustering-keys.html#micro-partitions-and-pruning\nSnowflake Documentation on Query Processing: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/queryingconcepts.html"
