              {
                "id": 488,
                "question": "A Query Profile shows a UnionAll operator with an extra Aggregate operator on top.\nWhat does this signify?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Exploding joins",
                  "B": "Inefficient pruning",
                  "C": "UNION without ALL",
                  "D": "Queries that are too large to fit in memory"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "C"
                ],
                "explanation": "The presence of an Aggregate operator atop a UnionAll operator in a Snowflake query profile strongly\nsuggests that a simple UNION (without the ALL keyword) was used in the query. Here's why:\nUNION ALL directly concatenates the result sets of the individual queries combined by the operator. It does\nnot perform any deduplication. Snowflake simply stacks the rows from each query on top of each other. This is\nefficient because it avoids extra processing.However, UNION (without ALL) implicitly performs deduplication. It removes duplicate rows from the\ncombined result set, which requires comparing all rows from all source queries. To achieve this deduplication,\nSnowflake adds an Aggregate operator. The Aggregate operator groups all identical rows, effectively\ncounting each distinct combination, and then returns the unique rows. This is computationally more expensive\nthan UNION ALL.\nOption A is incorrect because exploding joins typically manifest as Cartesian products or joins with\nsignificantly more output rows than input rows, not necessarily with an Aggregate operator after a UnionAll.\nOption B is incorrect because inefficient pruning usually impacts scan operators, making them read more data\nthan necessary; it doesn't directly create an Aggregate after a UnionAll. Option D is incorrect; while a query\nbeing too large might cause spillover to disk (indicated in other areas of the profile), the presence of an extra\nAggregate atop a UnionAll specifically points to the need for deduplication due to using UNION instead of\nUNION ALL.\nTherefore, the extra Aggregate operator atop the UnionAll serves as a clear indicator that UNION (which\nperforms deduplication) was used instead of the more efficient UNION ALL. Understanding Snowflake's query\nprofile and the differences between UNION and UNION ALL is crucial for optimizing query performance.\nRelevant resources:\nSnowflake Documentation on UNION: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/operatorscomparison.html#union-union-all-intersect-minus\nSnowflake Documentation on Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile.html"
              },
