                "explanation": "The correct answer is A. MONITOR. Here's why:\nThe question asks about the privilege required to view a load-monitoring chart related to a Snowflake virtual\nwarehouse. Load monitoring charts provide insights into warehouse performance, resource consumption, and\nquery execution metrics. To access this information, Snowflake employs a specific privilege control.\nThe MONITOR privilege grants a user the ability to view the status, metadata, and usage of Snowflake\nobjects, including virtual warehouses. This allows users with the MONITOR privilege to see the operational\ndata needed for load monitoring. They can observe metrics such as query latency, warehouse utilization, and\nresource consumption. MONITOR is a read-only privilege, aligned perfectly with the need to view information.\nMODIFY privilege allows for altering the configuration of a virtual warehouse. It enables actions such as\nresizing the warehouse or changing its properties. This doesn't align with merely viewing load monitoring\ncharts. The OPERATE privilege, in some cloud contexts, allows for starting, stopping or pausing a service.\nWhile related to warehouse management, it does not grant the right to view detailed load information. USAGE\nprivilege grants the ability to use a specific resource, like a database or schema. It doesn't necessarily give\naccess to performance monitoring data. Thus, USAGE alone isn't sufficient.\nTherefore, the MONITOR privilege is specifically designed to provide visibility into the performance and\nactivity of a Snowflake warehouse, making it the correct privilege needed to view a load-monitoring chart.\nSupporting Resources:\nSnowflake Documentation on Warehouse Security:https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/grantprivilege.html\nSnowflake Documentation on Usage Privilege:https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/sql/grant-privilege.html#usage-privilege"
