              {
                "id": 505,
                "question": "What common query issues can be identified using the Query Profile? (Choose two.)\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Data classification",
                  "B": "Exploding joins",
                  "C": "Unions",
                  "D": "Inefficient pruning",
                  "E": "Data masking"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "B",
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answers are B. Exploding joins and D. Inefficient pruning. The Snowflake Query Profile is a\npowerful tool for analyzing query performance and identifying bottlenecks.\nExploding joins (B) occur when a join operation produces a significantly larger result set than the input tables.\nThis can be identified in the Query Profile by examining the number of rows processed at each stage of the\nquery plan, specifically during join operations. A substantial increase in row count after a join indicates a\npotential \"exploding join,\" often caused by a missing or poorly chosen join condition, leading to Cartesian\nproducts and degraded performance.\nInefficient pruning (D) refers to the inability of Snowflake to effectively reduce the amount of data it reads\nfrom storage due to suboptimal filtering. In the Query Profile, you would look at scan operators or table\naccess portions. If Snowflake scans a substantial portion of the data when a more selective filter should have\nbeen applied, it points to inefficient pruning. This could be a result of incorrect filtering predicates, or nonoptimal use of partitioning and clustering.\nOptions A, C, and E are incorrect. While data classification (A) is an important security and governance aspect\nof data, it's not directly identified by the query profile, which focuses on execution. Unions (C) are standard\nSQL operators that don't inherently point to issues that the profile would highlight beyond general\ninefficiencies. Similarly, data masking (E) is a security measure that is not related to performance issues\nshown by the Query Profile. The Query Profile focuses on identifying performance issues in query execution,\nsuch as exploding joins and inefficient pruning, not data access controls or query logic.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Documentation - Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/ui/query-profile.html\nSnowflake Documentation - Understanding the Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/explain.html\nSnowflake Blog - Optimizing Query Performance: https://www.snowflake.com/blog/optimize-your-snowflake-queries-for-better-performance-and-cost/ ( This link provides general guidance on query\noptimization, including tips related to issues identified by the query profile)"
