                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is A. INTERSECT. The INTERSECT set operator in SQL, and specifically in Snowflake,\nreturns only the rows (or in this case, numeric values) that are found in both input tables or result sets. It\neffectively identifies the common elements between the two datasets. Options B, C, and D are incorrect in this\nscenario. MERGE is typically used for updating or inserting data based on matching conditions, not for findingcommon values. MINUS (also sometimes called EXCEPT) returns rows from the first table that are not present\nin the second, effectively finding the differences. UNION combines the rows from two tables, including\nduplicates with UNION ALL, or distinct rows with just UNION, but doesn't isolate only the shared elements.\nTherefore, if the goal is to identify numeric values present in both tables, INTERSECT is the appropriate set\noperator to use. Snowflake's SQL functionality provides robust support for set operations, aligning with\nstandard SQL practices.\nFor further research, you can consult the official Snowflake documentation on set operators:\nSnowflake Documentation on INTERSECT: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/operatorsset.html#intersect\nSnowflake Documentation on Set Operators: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/operatorsset.html"
