                "question": "What statistical information in a Query Profile indicates that the query is too large to fit in memory? (Choose two.)\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "Bytes spilled to local cache.",
                  "B": "Bytes spilled to local storage.",
                  "C": "Bytes spilled to remote cache.",
                  "D": "Bytes spilled to remote storage.",
                  "E": "Bytes spilled to remote metastore."
                },
                "answer": [
                  "B",
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is B and D: Bytes spilled to local storage and Bytes spilled to remote storage. These\nmetrics within a Snowflake Query Profile directly indicate that a query's intermediate result sets have\nexceeded the available memory allocated to the executing compute resources, thus requiring overflow to\ndisk.\nWhen a Snowflake query processes large datasets, the intermediate results, such as those produced during\njoins or aggregations, are initially held in memory for speed. If the data volume surpasses available RAM,\nSnowflake's query processing engine begins to 'spill' data. This spilling happens first to local storage\nassociated with the compute node where the query is running (option B). If this storage is insufficient, the\noverflow is directed to remote storage like an Amazon S3 bucket (option D) in cloud environments.\n'Bytes spilled to local cache' (option A) and 'Bytes spilled to remote cache' (option C) are related to caching\nmechanisms designed to improve performance by retrieving reusable data segments. They do not signify\nmemory pressure due to active query processing that exceeds memory limits. 'Bytes spilled to remote\nmetastore' (option E) refers to an entirely different context, involving metadata and not query data overflows.\nTherefore, when analyzing the Query Profile for memory-related issues, spilled bytes to local or remote\nstorage are the key indicators. This suggests the query size is too large for the available resources, leading to\na decline in performance as I/O operations are introduced. In summary, observing significant amounts of bytes\nspilled to either local or remote storage directly reveals the lack of adequate memory for the query\nprocessing.\nFurther Reading:Snowflake Documentation on Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile.html\nSnowflake Spilling: https://community.snowflake.com/s/article/What-is-Spilling-in-Snowflake"
