                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. STATEMENT_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS and E.\nSTATEMENT_QUEUED_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS. These are object-level parameters specifically\ndesigned to regulate query execution behavior within Snowflake.STATEMENT_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS defines the maximum duration a query is allowed to run\nbefore being automatically terminated by the system. This parameter helps prevent runaway\nqueries from consuming excessive resources and potentially impacting other operations. It\ndirectly controls processing time.\nSTATEMENT_QUEUED_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS sets the maximum time a query can remain in a\nqueue waiting for resources before it is canceled. This helps manage concurrency and avoids\nindefinite delays when the system is under heavy load. It controls how long a query waits, thus\ninfluencing concurrency handling.\nOptions A, B and C are not object-level parameters that directly influence query processing and\nconcurrency control.\nMAX_CONCURRENCY_LEVEL is primarily managed at the account or warehouse level, not\ndirectly at the object level. It dictates the maximum number of queries that can run concurrently\non a given warehouse.\nDATA_RETENTION_TIME_IN_DAYS and MIN_DATA_RETENTION_TIME_IN_DAYS are related to\nTime Travel and Fail-Safe data recovery features and don't control query processing directly.\nThey define the timeframe for which historical data is available and are not connected to query\nexecution flow or concurrency management. They are data management, not query processing\nparameters.\nIn summary, STATEMENT_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS and\nSTATEMENT_QUEUED_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS are the object-level parameters most relevant\nfor managing query runtime and wait times, thereby contributing to controlling processing and\nconcurrency at object level. Other options are related to other aspects of the Snowflake platform.\nFor further information, see these Snowflake documentation pages:\nObject Parameters: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/parameters.html#objectparameters\nSTATEMENT_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/parameters.html#statement-timeout-in-seconds\nSTATEMENT_QUEUED_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/parameters.html#statement-queued-timeout-in-seconds"
