                "question": "What are valid sub-clauses to the OVER clause for a window function? (Choose two.)\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "GROUP BY",
                  "B": "LIMIT",
                  "C": "ORDER BY",
                  "D": "PARTITION BY",
                  "E": "UNION ALL"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "C",
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct sub-clauses for the OVER clause in Snowflake window functions are ORDER BY and\nPARTITION BY.\nPARTITION BY divides the rows into partitions based on specified columns. Window functions then\noperate independently within each partition. This is crucial for tasks like calculating running\ntotals or ranking within categories, effectively isolating calculations to relevant subsets of data.\nIt's analogous to a GROUP BY clause, but without aggregating rows down, therefore maintaining\ndata dimensionality.\nORDER BY within the OVER clause determines the order in which the window function is applied\nto the rows within each partition. This is essential for functions that rely on a sequence, like\ncalculating moving averages or cumulative sums. Without an ORDER BY, the order of processing\nis arbitrary, hindering predictability.\nGROUP BY and LIMIT are not valid sub-clauses for OVER. GROUP BY is used for aggregation\noutside window functions. LIMIT is used for constraining the number of rows returned by the\nquery, and not relevant to window function operation within an OVER clause. UNION ALL\ncombines results of two or more queries, it is irrelevant here.\nTherefore, only ORDER BY and PARTITION BY are the correct options to define the windowing\nbehavior for the calculations inside.Authoritative links:\nSnowflake Documentation on Window Functions: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/functions-analytic\nSnowflake Documentation on the OVER clause: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/constructs/over-clause"
