                },
                "answer": [
                  "B",
                  "C"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answers are B and C. The Snowflake Query Profile is a powerful tool for analyzing\nquery execution and identifying performance bottlenecks. Exploding joins (B) occur when a join\noperation unexpectedly produces a significantly larger number of rows than either of the input\ntables. This leads to excessive processing and can severely impact query performance. The Query\nProfile visually highlights such situations through disproportionately large numbers of processed\nrows and the presence of a \"Join\" node that shows the row increase. Using the profile, users can\npinpoint the specific join contributing to the issue and then optimize the join conditions or the data\nitself. Common problems to look for in exploding joins include incorrect join keys, missing filters\nbefore the join or duplicate records in joined tables.\nFurthermore, the profile helps identify inefficient UNION operations, especially if UNION ALL was\nintended but UNION was used instead (C). UNION performs a deduplication step, which can be\ncomputationally expensive, especially on large datasets. The Query Profile can reveal if this\ndeduplication is the cause of query slow downs. Looking for the Union node in the plan, one can\nsee the number of input rows and the resulting output rows. If UNION is unnecessarily removing\nduplicate rows that were expected, this indicates the need to switch to UNION ALL. While theQuery Profile provides detailed information on query stages, operations, and their relative\nperformance, it does not directly reveal issues related to incorrect use of window functions (A),\nlarge distinct result sets (D), or problems with CTE structure (E) that have an overall impact on\nresult correctness. Although Window functions will appear in the query profile if present, it\ndoesn't directly flag whether they are being used incorrectly. Similarly, SELECT DISTINCT will be\npresent, but any potential slow down due to returning too many values will require manual\nassessment. Incorrect CTE implementation without a final select statement will cause an error\nbut not a performance issue diagnosable by the profile.\nAuthoritative Links:\nSnowflake Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile\nUnderstanding Joins in Snowflake: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/constructs/jointypes-syntax\nUNION vs UNION ALL in Snowflake: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/operators-set"
