                ],
                "explanation": "Query pruning in Snowflake, a crucial optimization technique, aims to reduce the amount of data\nthat needs to be scanned to fulfill a query, thus improving performance and lowering costs. The\neffectiveness of this pruning is directly reflected in the number of partitions involved in a query.\nAnalyzing \"Partitions scanned\" (A) and \"Partitions total\" (B) provides key insights. \"Partitions\ntotal\" represents the entire set of data partitions in the targeted table or tables. On the other\nhand, \"Partitions scanned\" indicates the actual number of partitions that Snowflake accessed andprocessed during query execution. A significant difference between the total and scanned\npartitions demonstrates effective query pruning. The less partitions scanned relative to the total\nnumber of partitions the more effective pruning is. Therefore, options A and B accurately\nrepresent the key statistics for evaluating the effects of query pruning.\nOptions C, D and E, while relevant to query performance, do not directly indicate the effectiveness\nof query pruning. \"Bytes scanned\" (C) refers to the total amount of data read from storage, which\ncan be affected by various factors beyond pruning and does not directly measure the benefit of\nthe pruning technique. \"Bytes read from result\" (D) represents the data sent to the user as the\nresult of the query, not the data scanned to process it. Lastly, \"Bytes written\" (E) is not relevant to\nthe initial data retrieval from the table, but relates to the query output or further operations.\nTherefore, options C, D, and E are not directly associated with evaluating the effectiveness of\nquery pruning.\nFor more information about pruning in Snowflake, consider reviewing the following resources:\nSnowflake Documentation on Query Profile: This section will show the scanned partitions metrics\nand allow you to review the pruning performance in a real world query:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile\nSnowflake Blog on Query Optimization: This may include details on query pruning strategies and\nimpact :https://www.snowflake.com/blog/"
