                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is C, Query pruning. Query pruning in Snowflake is a crucial performance\noptimization mechanism that intelligently reduces the amount of data scanned during query\nexecution. Snowflake stores data in micro-partitions, which are immutable storage units. Instead\nof scanning all micro-partitions, query pruning uses metadata about the data stored within them,\nlike min/max values and other statistics, to determine which micro-partitions are relevant to the\nquery's filter conditions (e.g., WHERE clause). This dramatically limits the number of micropartitions that Snowflake actually needs to read and process, significantly accelerating query\nperformance and reducing costs associated with data processing and storage retrieval. Caching\n(A) helps with repeated queries by storing previously accessed data in faster storage tiers, but\ndoesn't reduce the initial scan of micro-partitions. Cluster depth (B) refers to how deeply a table is\nclustered based on a specified clustering key, which impacts the order of data within the micropartitions but doesn't directly limit scans. Retrieval optimization (D) is a broader term that might\nencompass several techniques and isn't a specific Snowflake mechanism for limiting scanned\nmicro-partitions. Query pruning is the specific method that leverages metadata to exclude micropartitions that do not contain relevant data, directly impacting the amount of data read from disk.\nThis is a core feature that allows Snowflake to efficiently handle large datasets.\nFor further research, refer to the official Snowflake documentation:\nSearch Optimization Service: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/search-optimizationservice (while focused on search optimization, it discusses pruning concepts)\nUnderstanding Snowflake Table Structures: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tablesstructure (provides background on micro-partitions)\nClustering Keys: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/tables-clustering-keys (explains how\nclustering works, impacting pruning)"
