                "explanation": "The correct answer is A, using the RESULT_SCAN function. The SHOW FILE FORMATS command,\nlike many other SHOW commands in Snowflake, returns its output as a table-like result set. This\nresult isn't directly a table that you can query using standard SQL. Instead, it's a transient result\navailable in the user session. To process this data as you would a regular table, you must utilize\nRESULT_SCAN. RESULT_SCAN allows you to treat the output of a SHOW command (or the result\nof any statement that produces a result set) as a virtual table that you can then query with\nstandard SQL syntax. Options B, C, and D are not valid methods for processing the results of a\nSHOW command in Snowflake. Creating a cursor (Option B) is typically used for iterative\nprocessing of data within stored procedures, not for querying the direct result of a SHOW\ncommand. Placing the command in the FROM clause in brackets (Option C) is not recognized SQL\nsyntax in Snowflake. Assigning the command to a RESULTSET variable (Option D) is relevant tostored procedures but isn't the way to access the data for immediate querying. The\nRESULT_SCAN function provides the specific mechanism to transform the transient, result-set of\nthe SHOW command into a queryable virtual table, thus enabling post-processing with SQL. This\nallows you to filter the result, select specific columns, join with other tables, and perform other\nstandard SQL operations. Using RESULT_SCAN to post-process SHOW command outputs is a\ncommon practice in Snowflake for data analysis and automation.\nAuthoritative Link:\nSnowflake Documentation on RESULT_SCAN: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/functions/result_scan\nSnowflake Documentation on SHOW commands: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/show"
