                "explanation": "The correct answer is C and D: \"Bytes spilled to local storage\" and \"Bytes spilled to\nremote storage.\" These metrics within a Snowflake Query Profile directly indicate that\nintermediate results exceeded available memory during query processing. When a query\ngenerates intermediate data larger than what can be held in memory, Snowflake begins\n\"spilling\" this data to disk. Spilling to local storage, usually SSDs attached to the\ncompute nodes, is the first resort. If local storage also fills up, Snowflake further spills\nto remote storage, typically cloud object storage (like AWS S3, Azure Blob Storage, or\nGoogle Cloud Storage). This spilling signifies a performance penalty, as disk I/O is\nsignificantly slower than memory access. Increased bytes spilled to either local or\nremote storage indicate that the query likely needs optimization or a larger warehouse\nsize to handle the workload within memory limits. Conversely, \"Bytes scanned,\"\n\"Partitions scanned,\" and \"Percentage scanned from cache\" are related to the input data\nbeing accessed, not the size of the intermediate results. These metrics describe how\nefficiently Snowflake reads data from its storage layer. Therefore, they don't\nspecifically point towards memory overflow during processing. They are related to data\nretrieval, not data storage during the query execution.\nFurther Research:\nSnowflake Documentation on Query Profiles: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/ui/queryprofile.html This page provides detailed explanations of each metric visible within the\nSnowflake Query Profile.\nSnowflake Documentation on Query Execution: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/querying-concepts.html This section gives an overview of the query processing\nlifecycle within Snowflake which helps to understand the context of memory usage.\nSnowflake Blog on Query Optimization: (Search the official blog for relevant articles onspill and query optimization). The snowflake blog provides numerous articles on\noptimizing queries for better performance and how to understand and address spills"
