                  "A": "QUALIFY",
                  "B": "LATERAL",
                  "C": "PIVOT",
                  "D": "CONNECT BY"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is D. CONNECT BY. Snowflake, unlike some traditional relational\ndatabases, does not have explicit support for Common Table Expressions (CTEs) with\nrecursive definitions. Instead, it provides the CONNECT BY clause to achieve hierarchicalor recursive data querying. CONNECT BY is a proprietary syntax used to traverse parentchild relationships within a single table. This clause starts from a root row and then\niteratively follows the relationship defined in the CONNECT BY condition. This is\nessential for handling data organized in trees or graphs, such as organizational\nstructures, bill of materials, or network topologies. The other options, QUALIFY,\nLATERAL, and PIVOT, serve different purposes. QUALIFY is used to filter results based\non window functions. LATERAL allows subqueries to reference columns from previous\nFROM clauses, typically used for complex data manipulations. PIVOT transforms rows\ninto columns, which is unsuitable for recursive data exploration. Therefore, CONNECT\nBY is the specific mechanism within Snowflake designed to handle queries that explore\nrecursive or hierarchical data structures. The clause supports conditions like PRIOR to\nreference the parent row values in order to traverse the structure correctly and to\nprevent infinite loops. These functionalities are core to retrieving data organized\nrecursively.\nRelevant Snowflake documentation can be found here:\nCONNECT BY: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/constructs/connect-by\nQUALIFY: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/constructs/qualify\nLATERAL: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/constructs/lateral\nPIVOT: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/constructs/pivot"
