                "id": 1129,
                "question": "Which Query Profile operator is considered a DML operator?\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "ExternalScan",
                  "B": "Flatten",
                  "C": "Merge",
                  "D": "Sort"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "C"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is C, Merge. Within Snowflake's Query Profile, operators represent\nthe steps taken to execute a query. DML (Data Manipulation Language) operators are\nthose that modify data within tables. Merge is a DML operation used to insert, update, or\ndelete data based on matching conditions between a source and target table. It's a\ncombined operation that performs all of these manipulations within a single statement.\nExternalScan (A) reads data from external sources without modifying Snowflake data.\nFlatten (B) transforms semi-structured data into relational rows, also not a DML\noperation. Sort (D) rearranges data order, which also doesn't modify the stored data.\nTherefore, among the options, only Merge directly impacts the data in a table, making it\na DML operator. The other listed operators primarily handle data retrieval and\ntransformation for processing without changing the underlying data storage.\nUnderstanding the distinction between DDL, DML, and DQL operations is essential when\nanalyzing query performance and data modification within Snowflake.\nFor further research:\nSnowflake documentation on MERGE: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/sqlreference/sql/merge.html\nSnowflake documentation on Query Profile: https://docs.snowflake.com/en/userguide/ui-query-profile.html\nGeneral concept of DML, DDL, and DQL:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_manipulation_language"
              },
