                "explanation": "The correct answer is B. RESULT_SCAN.\nThe RESULT_SCAN table function in Snowflake allows you to access and process the\nresults of a previously executed query. It retrieves the result set of a specified query ID.\nThis enables you to perform further analysis, aggregation, or transformation on the data\nthat was already retrieved by the initial query, without re-executing the original query.\nQUERY_HISTORY and QUERY_HISTORY_BY_SESSION (options A and D) provide\nmetadata about past queries, like start time, end time, user, and SQL text. They don't\nprovide access to the results of those queries. DESCRIBE_RESULTS (option C) is not a\nvalid Snowflake function.\nThe ability to access and manipulate query results through RESULT_SCAN is beneficial\nin several scenarios. For example, you might use it to apply a window function to a set of\nresults retrieved by a simpler query, or to consolidate data that comes from multiple\nseparate queries into a single result set. It helps optimize resource utilization and\nperformance by avoiding redundant data retrieval. Using RESULT_SCAN, you can\ndirectly build on the results of a previous query instead of re-running the base query\nagain, potentially reducing processing time and cost. It also facilitates complex data\nmanipulation by chaining query processing steps.\nFor further details on RESULT_SCAN, refer to the Snowflake documentation:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/functions/result_scan.html"
