                "question": "Using which object-level parameters will help limit query processing and concurrency slowdowns? (Choose two.)\n",
                "choices": {
                  "A": "MULTI_STATEMENT_COUNT",
                  "B": "ENABLE_QUERY_ACCELERATION",
                  "C": "STATEMENT_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS",
                  "D": "STATEMENT_QUEUED_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS",
                  "E": "QUERY_ACCELERATION_MAX_SCALE_FACTOR"
                },
                "answer": [
                  "C",
                  "D"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is C and D: STATEMENT_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS and\nSTATEMENT_QUEUED_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS. These parameters directly control the\nlifespan of queries and how long they can wait in the queue, respectively, contributing to\npreventing query processing and concurrency slowdowns.\nSTATEMENT_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS dictates the maximum time a query can execute.\nIf a query exceeds this limit, it is automatically terminated, preventing it from consuming\nresources indefinitely and potentially blocking other queries. This helps in addressing\nrunaway queries or poorly optimized queries that could otherwise bog down the system.\nSTATEMENT_QUEUED_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS defines the maximum time a query will\nremain in the queue waiting for resources. If this timeout is reached, the query is\ncancelled. This parameter is crucial in preventing a build-up of queries waiting for\nresources, which can happen under heavy load. By automatically canceling queries that\nhave been waiting too long, Snowflake can better prioritize active queries and maintainoverall system responsiveness. Without this timeout, a backlog of queued queries could\nstarve new queries, leading to significant performance degradation.\nOption A, MULTI_STATEMENT_COUNT, relates to the number of statements that can be\nexecuted within a multi-statement request and doesn't directly affect query slowdowns.\nOption B, ENABLE_QUERY_ACCELERATION, is intended to speed up queries that meet\nspecific criteria using cloud services and resources specifically for query optimization.\nWhile this can mitigate some slowdowns, it's a performance enhancement rather than a\ndirect limiter. Option E, QUERY_ACCELERATION_MAX_SCALE_FACTOR, governs the\nmaximum scale factor for the query acceleration service, essentially controlling the\ndegree of acceleration that can be applied. While related to performance, it doesn’t\ndirectly limit processing time or queue time like C and D.\nTherefore, STATEMENT_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS and\nSTATEMENT_QUEUED_TIMEOUT_IN_SECONDS are the most relevant parameters for\nlimiting query processing time and preventing concurrency slowdowns by actively\nmanaging query execution and queuing. They offer a direct method for controlling\nresource consumption and maintaining a responsive system under load.\nRefer to the Snowflake documentation for more information on these parameters:\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/sql-reference/parameters#object-parameters\nhttps://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/query-acceleration-service"
