                },
                "answer": [
                  "B"
                ],
                "explanation": "The correct answer is B, ExternalScan. Query profiles in Snowflake are invaluable tools\nfor performance tuning and understanding query execution. The ExternalScan operator\nspecifically focuses on reading data from external stages like Amazon S3, Google Cloud\nStorage, or Azure Blob Storage. Pruning efficiency directly relates to how effectively\nSnowflake can filter out unnecessary partitions or files during the read operation from\nthese external sources. A high pruning efficiency means Snowflake is reading only the\nrequired data, minimizing I/O and improving performance. The ExternalScan operator's\ndetails show how many files were considered versus how many were actually scanned,\nindicating the effectiveness of pruning. The TableScan operator relates to data read\nfrom Snowflake tables, while InternalObject is often associated with metadata or\ninternal data handling. Generator nodes are generally for creating data on the fly. While\nTableScan can be affected by micro-partition pruning, ExternalScan directly reflects the\nefficiency of pruning operations performed on the external data source based on the\nquery's filter conditions and the partitioning scheme of the external data. LowExternalScan pruning efficiency suggests issues like missing or insufficient partitioning,\ninefficient data formats, or inadequate statistics on the external data. Investigating the\nstatistics collected from external data is useful for helping with query pruning.\nImproving pruning efficiency for ExternalScan operations can significantly reduce query\nexecution time and cost. Therefore, ExternalScan directly presents pruning efficiency\ninformation, making it the correct answer.\nHere's a resource for more information on Snowflake Query\nProfiles:https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/ui-query-profile.html"
